INSERT INTO `codes` (`id`, `body`, `reference_id`, `notes`, `pages`, `deleted_at`, `created_at`, `updated_at`) VALUES
(1, '<blockquote><p>This definition elucidates Schelling\'s general principle: \"This generally acknowledged and wholly undeniable objectivity of intellectual intuition is art itself. For aesthetic intuition is nothing other than intellectual intuition become objective.\"</p></blockquote>', 1, NULL, '152', '2021-02-22 08:58:55', '2021-02-07 18:05:15', '2021-02-22 08:58:55'),
(2, '<p>For Fanon, the colonized world is compartmentalized, a world of colonizer and a native. The dichotomy remains between the outsider and insider:</p><blockquote><p>It is not the factories, the estates, or the bank account which primarily characterize the \"ruling class.\" The ruling species is first and foremost the outsider from elsewhere, different from the indigenous population, \"the others.\" </p><p></p></blockquote>', 2, NULL, '5', NULL, '2021-02-07 18:50:41', '2021-02-07 18:50:41'),
(3, '<p>The colonizer represents the colonized as the absolute evil:</p><blockquote><p>The \"native\" is declared impervious to ethics, representing not only the absence of values but also the negation of values. He is, dare we say it, the enemy of values. (6) ... Values are, in fact, irreversibly poisoned and infected as soon as they come into contact with the colonized. The customs of the colonized, their traditions, their myths, especially their myths, are the very mark of this indigence and innate depravity.</p></blockquote>', 2, NULL, '6', NULL, '2021-02-07 18:59:39', '2021-02-07 18:59:39'),
(4, '<p>The supremacy of white values is stated with such violence, the victorious confrontation of these values with the lifestyle and beliefs of the colonized is so impregnated with aggressiveness, that as a counter measure the colonized rightly make a mockery of them whenever they are mentioned. In the colonial context the colonist only quits undermining the colonized once the latter have proclaimed loud and clear that white values reign supreme. In the period of decolonization the colonized masses thumb their noses at these very values, shower them with insults and vomit them up.</p>', 2, NULL, '8', NULL, '2021-02-07 19:11:34', '2021-02-07 19:11:34'),
(5, '<p>The idea of westoxification:</p><blockquote><p>The intellectual who, for his part, has adopted the abstract, universal values of the colonizer is prepared to fight so that colonist and colonized can live in peace in a new world. But what he does not see, because precisely colonialism and all its modes of thought have seeped into him, is that the colonist is no longer interested in staying and coexisting once the colonial context disappeared.</p></blockquote>', 2, NULL, '9', NULL, '2021-02-07 19:21:40', '2021-02-07 19:21:40'),
(6, '<blockquote><p>The colonized intellectual accepted the cogency of these ideas and there in the back of his mind stood a sentinel on duty guarding the Greco-Roman pedestal. But during the struggle for liberation, when the colonized intellectual touches base again with his people, the artificial sentinel is smashed to smithereens. All the Mediterranean values, the triumph of the individual, of enlightenment and Beauty turn into pale, lifeless trinkets.</p></blockquote>', 2, NULL, '11', NULL, '2021-02-07 22:55:50', '2021-02-07 22:55:50'),
(7, '<p>Fanon against individualism and other western enlightenment ideals:</p><blockquote><p>The colonized intellectual learned from his masters that the individual must assert himself. ...Involvement in the organization of the struggle will already introduce him to a different vocabulary. \"Brother,\" \"sister,\" \"comrade\" are words outlawed by the colonialist bourgeoisie because in their thinking my brother is my wallet and my comrade, my scheming.</p></blockquote>', 2, NULL, '11', NULL, '2021-02-07 23:03:33', '2021-02-07 23:03:33'),
(8, '<p>why the colonized intellectual fails according to Fanon. He does assimilate with the colonialist bourgeoisie way of thinking:</p><blockquote><p>For he is unable to make himself inessential when confronted with a purpose or idea. ...He is then constantly at risk of becoming a demagogue. ...He turns into a kind of mimic man who nods his assent to every word by the people, transformed by him into an arbiter of truth. ...But the fellah, the unemployed and the starving do not lay claim to truth. They do not say they represent the truth because they are the truth in very being. </p></blockquote>', 2, NULL, '13', NULL, '2021-02-07 23:24:06', '2021-02-07 23:24:06'),
(9, '<p>A world compartmentalized, Manichaean and petrified, a world of statues: the statue of the general who led the conquest, the statue of the engineer who built the bridge.</p>', 2, NULL, '15', NULL, '2021-02-07 23:59:11', '2021-02-07 23:59:11'),
(10, '<blockquote><p>But deep down the colonized subject acknowledge no authority. he is dominated but not domesticated. He is made to feel inferior, but by no means convinced of his inferiority.</p></blockquote><p>The colonized is the man of action due to oppression according to Fanon.</p>', 2, NULL, '16', NULL, '2021-02-08 00:08:50', '2021-02-08 00:08:50'),
(11, '<blockquote><p>The relationship between colonist and colonized is one of physical mass. Against the greater number the colonist pits his force. The colonist is an exhibitionist.</p></blockquote>', 2, NULL, '17', NULL, '2021-02-08 00:34:50', '2021-02-08 00:34:50'),
(12, '<p>Fiercely against superstition, Fanon writes:</p><p>The magical, supernatural powers prove to be surprisingly ego boosting. The colonist\'s powers are infinitely shrink, stamped by foreignness. There is no real reason to fight them because what really matters is that the mythical structures contain far more terrifying adversaries. It is evident that everything is reduced to a permanent confrontation at the level of phantasy.</p>', 2, NULL, '19', NULL, '2021-02-08 01:06:48', '2021-02-08 01:06:48'),
(13, '<p>Fanon\'s reference to <em>mujahedin:</em></p><p>Giving food to the mujahedin...such are the practical tasks the people are asked to undertake in liberation struggle.</p>', 2, NULL, '19', NULL, '2021-02-08 01:09:07', '2021-02-08 01:09:07'),
(14, '<p>In the colonial world, the colonized\'s affectivity is kept on edge like a running sore flinching from a caustic agent. ...Another aspect of the colonized\'s affectivity can be seen when it is drained of energy by ecstasy of dance. ... (19) One step further and we find ourselves in deep possession. In actual fact, these are organized seances of possession and dispossession... Such a disintegration, dissolution or splitting of the personality, plays a key regulating role in ensuing the stability of the colonized world.</p>', 2, NULL, '20', NULL, '2021-02-08 01:19:23', '2021-02-08 01:19:23'),
(15, '<p>In his analysis, Fanon shifts his emphasis from the working class to the peasants, which signals a Maoist turn.</p><blockquote><p>The peasantry is systematically left out of most of the nationalist parties\' propaganda. But it is obvious that in colonials countries only the peasantry is revolutionary.</p></blockquote>', 2, NULL, '23', NULL, '2021-02-08 03:50:56', '2021-02-08 03:50:56'),
(16, '<p>The monopolistic fraction of the metropolitan bourgeoisie will not support a government whose policy is based solely on the power of arms. What the metropolitan financiers and industrialists expect is not the devastation of the colonial population but the protection of their \"legitimate interest\" using economic agreement.  </p>', 2, NULL, '27', NULL, '2021-02-08 04:19:48', '2021-02-08 04:19:48'),
(17, '<blockquote><p>It is therefore a diplomacy in motion, in range, which contrasts strangely with the petrified, motionless world of colonization.</p></blockquote>', 2, NULL, '37', NULL, '2021-02-09 02:09:18', '2021-02-09 02:09:18'),
(18, '<blockquote><p>Dewey begins his lecture on artistic form with a discussion of experience and environment that seeks to strengthen his more general philosophical claim that works of art are not stand-alone \"objects\" so much as mediating means for and the consummation of activities fully situated whiten  the experimental world. As part of this, he speaks directly of form as an outcome of the interaction between self and the environment.</p></blockquote>', 5, NULL, '103', NULL, '2021-02-12 21:08:24', '2021-02-12 21:08:24'),
(19, '<p>As Barletta argues, Dewey views the environment as a constitutive element of the form:</p><blockquote><p>Dewey\'s argument is that form is properly seen as a productive tension sustained by two sources of energy--one emanating from the organism (however defined) and the other from an environment (which Dewey goes to great pains to define) that is something external to the organism.</p></blockquote>', 5, NULL, '104', NULL, '2021-02-12 21:20:10', '2021-02-12 21:20:10'),
(20, '<blockquote><p>What remains constant is the notion of interaction, of a productive tension--the outcome of which is never certain--out of which both experience and form emerges.</p></blockquote>', 5, NULL, '107', NULL, '2021-02-12 21:35:21', '2021-02-12 21:35:21'),
(21, '<p>To begin with, Dewey\'s presentation of rhythm is of a piece with his earlier contention that \"there is rhythm in nature before poetry, painting, architecture and music exist.\" ([1934] 2005, 141). It finds even more deliberate expression in his historical account of the development of art and artistic rhythm out of human interaction with the various tools, forces, and materials of the surrounding environment.</p>', 5, NULL, '108', NULL, '2021-02-12 22:14:38', '2021-02-12 22:14:38'),
(22, '<blockquote><p>Dewey argues that rhythm has its roots in nature and in human intimacy with cyclical and measured changes in the natural environment. From this primordial relation, there was--as he has it--a gradual expansion and subsequent application of the principle of a natural \"ordered variation of changes\" to non-natural domain and activities.</p></blockquote>', 5, NULL, '109', NULL, '2021-02-12 22:33:28', '2021-02-12 22:33:28'),
(23, '<p>Dewey\'s arument is that our ancestors did not imitate nature so much as recontextualize their interactional relation to it within new cultural (e.g. artistic) domain.</p>', 5, NULL, '110', NULL, '2021-02-12 22:38:08', '2021-02-12 22:38:08'),
(24, '<p>As part of what Dewey would later refer to as \"situation,\" rhythm exists \"prior to, neutral to, and inclusive of, any distinction and relation that can be legitimately instituted between subject and object\" ([1934], 2008, 70). It comes on the scene, in this sense, prior to judgement or even cognition; it is, for Dewey, an integral part of the kinetic and indivisible relation between organism and environment that serves as the ground for experience.</p>', 5, NULL, '110-111', NULL, '2021-02-12 22:56:22', '2021-02-12 22:56:22'),
(25, '<blockquote><p>\'\"Je pense done je suis,\' ecrivait Descartes. La remarque en a deja ete faite, on pense toujours quelque chose. Le Negro-africain pourrait dire: \'Je sens l\'Autre, je danse l\'Autre, done je suis.\' Or danser, c\'est creer, surtout lorsque la danse est danse d\'amour. C\'est en tout cas, le meilleur mode de la connaissance\" (\"I think therefore I am,\" wrote Descartes. On this, the point has already been made: we always think something. The Black African might say: \"I sense the Other, I dance the Other, therefore I am.\" And to dance is to create, above all when the dance is one of love. This is, in any case, the best form of knowing; Senghor 1964, 259).</p></blockquote><p>Senghor, Léopold Sédar. 1964. Liberté. Paris: Seuil.</p>', 5, NULL, '111-2', NULL, '2021-02-12 23:06:36', '2021-02-12 23:06:36'),
(26, '<p>One must point out that Black Africans, if they never stress the individual, do not similarly neglect the person. The person emerges less in the search for singularity than in the deepening and intensification of spiritual life. [ ... ] In Black Africa, one is linked to the object of property, as I have already stated, through the legal bond of custom, as ,vell as-and abo,,e all-by a mystical bond. One feels oneself to be a person-part of a clan, I admit-when faced with the object of property, which is, in turn, felt as a person. In this way, o,vnership of the means of production is no longer abstract or illusory. The worker feels that they are not a simple component of their land or work. They feel, they know that their intelligence and their arms work freely on something alive and of some good to them. (269-70)</p><p>Senghor, Léopold Sédar. 1959. “Éléments constructifs d’une civilisation d’inspiration négro-africaine.” Présence africaine 24–25: 249–79. </p>', 5, NULL, '113', NULL, '2021-02-13 00:28:12', '2021-02-13 00:28:12'),
(27, '<p>For Sanghor, the connection between the structuring relation between the self and community is rhythm.</p><blockquote><p>What is the ontological glue that binds a woman to her neighbor? For Sanghor, the answer is rhythm.</p></blockquote>', 5, NULL, '113', NULL, '2021-02-13 00:31:09', '2021-02-13 00:31:09'),
(28, '<blockquote><p>Senghor\'s take on rhythm and Western thought points to something foundational and potentially disconcerting: we are not in control, at least not as much as we would like to believe, of the process by which we live and repeatedly give meaning to our experience. While Dewey seeks to heal the philosophical rift forged between the human \"organism\'\' and the environing world, his invocation of rhythm--still wholly the product of an analogous philosophical rift between form, ethics, ... In this, Senghor is right to point to a \"betrayal\" of Greek thought and likewise right to point to the possibility of rhythm, from an African point of view, as the \"architecture\" of being, as the very structure or form of being in the world. As such, rhythm serves as a radical limit on human agency; it is, in essence, a primordial dispossession. That is, environment is not only something with which we inevitably interact; it also something much more powerful and even entraining- a force that brings us into form. This is what Dewey perhaps points to but cannot say.</p></blockquote>', 5, NULL, '115', NULL, '2021-02-13 00:38:47', '2021-02-13 00:38:47'),
(29, '<p>Senghor makes a broad claims for his account of rhythm as ontological, speaking of a generalized \"African\" point of view on the matter: \"Je sens l\'Autre, je danse l\'Autre, donc je suis.\" (I sense the Other, I dance the Other, therefore I am.)</p>', 5, NULL, '115', NULL, '2021-02-13 00:43:38', '2021-02-13 00:43:38'),
(30, '<blockquote><p>in the 1960s, Mehdi Husseini, previously known for his reliably abstract oil paintings, began illustrating household objects such as dish racks and air conditioners. At the same time, a fellow artist named Behjat Sadr began riffing on imported Venetian blinds as objects of art; and Coca-Cola bottles to serve as inspiration for Parvaneh Etemadi.</p></blockquote>', 7, NULL, '2', NULL, '2021-02-15 00:25:58', '2021-02-15 00:25:58'),
(31, '<p>With the increase in oil revenues in the late 1960s and 1970s, the class-based communities soon gave way to a more homogenous consumer society, consisting largely of the working and middle-class.</p>', 7, NULL, '13', NULL, '2021-02-15 04:20:11', '2021-02-15 04:20:11'),
(32, '<p>Something as simple as new ways of cleaning the house can be traced to America\'s exercise of \"quiet diplomacy\" in Iran.</p>', 7, NULL, '14', NULL, '2021-02-15 04:23:43', '2021-02-15 04:23:43'),
(33, '<blockquote><p>After WWII, the Truman administration\'s Point IV Program exported American home life, establishing home-economics schools for Iranian girls, which included, not only new curricula, but also actual model homes. Over the next couple decades, US exports to Iran expanded to the point that, by the second half of the 1970s, the Iranian market was saturated with American products, These were increasingly advertised in the popular press and women\'s magazines.</p></blockquote>', 7, NULL, '14', NULL, '2021-02-15 04:33:45', '2021-02-15 04:33:45'),
(34, '<p>A/r/tography, an arts-based research methodology, emphasizes the process (praxis) through through which practitioners draw upon their Artist, Researcher, and Teacher identities to artistically engage (poesis) in research and (re)questioning their understandings (theoria). Springgay, Irwin, and Kind (2005)</p>', 9, NULL, '3', NULL, '2021-02-19 03:52:36', '2021-02-19 03:52:36'),
(35, '<p>the moment of silence spoke loudly as our original research</p><p>questions evolved (Irwin, 2008) through the experience of theatrically reflecting upon the</p><p>data. Irwin (2008) suggests “it may be that in rhizomatic form, various individuals within the</p><p>community will come to different understandings” (p. 77).</p>', 9, NULL, '5', NULL, '2021-02-19 04:12:17', '2021-02-19 04:12:17'),
(36, '<p>A/r/tographic contiguity emphasises a “coming together” to foster interrelatedness and to</p><p>“make visible the spaces in between” (Springgay et al., 2005, p. 900).</p>', 12, NULL, '900', NULL, '2021-02-19 04:24:12', '2021-02-19 04:24:12'),
(37, '<p>Aime Cesaire\'s letter to Maurice Thorez, the General Secretary of the French Communist Party, speaks of disillusionment and despair of Cesaire. He writes: \"From now on, they will show up as watermarks in the very substance of the system, as the obsession behind our feeling of failure and humiliation.</p>', 14, NULL, '145', NULL, '2021-02-21 03:11:34', '2021-02-21 03:11:34'),
(38, '<p>One fact that is paramount in my eyes is this: we, men of color, at this precise moment in our historical evolution, have come to grasp, in our consciousness, the full breadth of our singularity, and are ready to assume on all levels and in all  areas the responsibilities that flows from this coming to consciousness. </p><p>The singularity of our \"situation in the world,\" which cannot be confused with any other. The singularity of our problems, which cannot be reduced to any other problem. The singularity of our history, constructed out of terrible misfortunes that belong to no one else. The singularity of our culture, which we which we wish to live in a way that is more and more real.</p>', 14, NULL, '147', NULL, '2021-02-21 03:21:42', '2021-02-21 03:21:42'),
(39, '<p>In any case, it is clear that our struggle--the struggle of colonial people against colonialism, the struggle of peoples of color against racism--is more complex, or better yet, of a completely different nature than the fight of the French worker against French capitalism, and it cannot in any way be considered a part, a fragment, of the struggle.</p>', 14, NULL, '147', NULL, '2021-02-21 03:29:10', '2021-02-21 03:29:10'),
(40, '<blockquote><p>Not at all. I am not burying myself in a narrow particularism. But neither do I want to lose myself in an emancipated universalism. There are two ways to lose oneself: walled segregation in the particular or dilution in the \"universal.\"</p></blockquote>', 14, NULL, '152', NULL, '2021-02-21 05:48:41', '2021-02-21 05:48:41'),
(41, '<blockquote><p>There is a veritable Copernican revolution to be imposed here, so ingrained in Europe (from the extremes right to the extreme left) is the habit of doing for us, arranging for us, thinking for us--in short, the habit of challenging our possession of this right to initiative of which I have just spoken, which is, at the end of the day, the right to personality.</p></blockquote>', 14, NULL, '150', NULL, '2021-02-21 05:54:04', '2021-02-21 05:54:04'),
(42, '<p>The Congress of Cultural Freedom (CCF) was funded by the CIA:</p><blockquote><p>From 1951 onward, the CCF, which had mostly confined itself to the ideological struggle in Europe, started to engage with the emerging states of Asia. While the congress would later find itself engulfed in scandal over its funding from the Central Intelligence Agency...</p><p>...</p><p>The congress mostly rean tot he political Left, and the paradoxicalnature of instrumental political sponsorship, intellectual freedom, and efficacy of that freedom as an anti-Communist weapon has been well studied.</p></blockquote>', 15, NULL, '57', NULL, '2021-02-21 07:04:36', '2021-02-21 07:04:36'),
(43, '<blockquote><p>Example passage from the reading.</p></blockquote>', 17, NULL, '14', NULL, '2021-02-22 22:43:28', '2021-02-22 22:43:28'),
(44, '<p>If we follow Dewey, Arendt, Biesta or didaktik theory, teaching in physical education has the</p><p>responsibility to engage students in practices that bring something unexpected, bringing newness</p><p>not asked for. In this sense, transformative learning and teaching is not about changing the child</p><p>or the young. It is instead about opening up different ways of being in the world and forming teaching</p><p>so everyone’s beginnings are allowed to come into being. But what does this look like?</p>', 18, NULL, '619', NULL, '2021-02-23 15:24:41', '2021-02-23 15:24:41'),
(45, '<blockquote><p>... I draw attention to what I called \"Life-line of imperialism.\" This line runs from the Straits of Gilbraltar, through the Mediterranean, the Suez Canal, the Red Sea, the Indian Ocean, the South China Sea and the Sea of Japan. For most of that enormous, the territories on both sides of this lifeline were colonies, the people were unfree, their future mortgaged to an alien system. Along that life-line, that main artery of imperialism, there was pumped the life-blood of colonialism.</p></blockquote>', 19, NULL, '41-42', NULL, '2021-02-23 20:28:51', '2021-02-23 20:28:51'),
(46, '<p>We are of many different nations, we are of many different social backgrounds and cultural patterns. Our ways of life are different. Our national characters, or colours or motifs--call it what you will--are different. Our racial stock is different, and even the color of our skin is different. But what does that matters? Mankind is united or divided by considerations other than these. Conflict comes not from variety by considerations other than these. Conflict comes not from variety of skins, nor from variety of religion, but from variety of desires.</p>', 19, NULL, '43', NULL, '2021-02-23 20:51:38', '2021-02-23 20:51:38'),
(47, '<p>Colonialism has also its modern dress, in the form of economic control, intellectual control, actual physical control by a small but alien community within a nation. It is a skillful and determined enemy, and it does not give up its loot easily.</p>', 19, NULL, '44', NULL, '2021-02-23 21:34:34', '2021-02-23 21:34:34'),
(48, '<p>We cannot indulge in power politics. Diplomacy for us is not a matter of the big stick. Our statesmen, by and large, are not back with serried ranks of jet bombers. What can we do? We can do much! We can inject voice of reason into world affairs. We can mobilize all the spiritual, all the moral, all the political strength of Asia and Africa on the side of peace.</p>', 19, NULL, '45-6', NULL, '2021-02-23 22:01:19', '2021-02-23 22:01:19'),
(49, '<p>But what harm is in diversity, when there is unity in desire? ... Therefore, it behooves us to take particular care to ensure that the principle which is usually called the \"Live and let live\"--mark, I don not say the principle of \"Laissez faire, laissez passer\" of Liberalism which is obsolete--is first of all applied by the most completely within our own Asian and African frontiers.</p>', 19, NULL, '45', NULL, '2021-02-23 23:04:19', '2021-02-23 23:04:19'),
(50, '<p>So, let this Asian-African Conference be a great success! Make the \"Live and let live\" principle and the \"Unity in Diversity\" motto the unifying force which brings us all together--to seek in friendly, uninhibited discussion, ways and means by which each of us can live his own life, in their own way, in harmony, and in peace.</p>', 19, NULL, '49', NULL, '2021-02-23 23:25:31', '2021-02-23 23:25:31'),
(51, '<p>\"Modernism,\" as the aesthetics of modernity and an art historical discourse, has been conceived in the West exclusively about the West and for the westerner as ultimate reader, spectator, and consumer.</p>', 20, NULL, '25', NULL, '2021-02-24 08:02:54', '2021-02-24 08:02:54'),
(52, '<blockquote><p>Ziapour had studied at the Faculty of Fine Arts, which, in my view, was just as pluralist in its approach as the period itself. Heydarian, the classicist, was one of his teachers, but the director Andre Godard and two of the teachers were French and their pedagogical emphasis--a pseudo Beaux-Arts system--was now on imagination rather than servitude to nature. </p></blockquote>', 20, NULL, 'footenote 16, 41', NULL, '2021-02-24 19:16:52', '2021-02-24 19:16:52'),
(53, '<blockquote><p>Ziapour exhibited the painting [<em>Kaveh\'s Uprising</em>] at VOKS (the Iran-Soviet Cultural Society) in 1946 just prior his departure for Paris. The exhibition was widely inclusive, a pluralist enterprise, and one may say egalitarian in terms of mediums. It features a variety of schools and styles, ranging from the \"classical\" (Kamal-al-Molk) to young painters (Kazemi, Vishkai, Ziapour), and interestingly, a section on embroideries by women (<em>souzan douzi</em> by Malekara Lhajehnouri, Maliheh Saidi), miniature painting (Hossein Behzad), and even caricatures represented by Frederic Talberg, a Swedish immigrant.</p></blockquote>', 20, NULL, 'footenote 16, 41', NULL, '2021-02-24 19:24:58', '2021-02-24 19:24:58'),
(54, '<p>The rooster on the periodical\'s cover designed by Ziapour was an emblematic call to awakening, a reference to \"cock-a-doodle-do,\" the first line of Nima Youshij\'s poem printed in the first issue and perhaps a nod to the Gallic cock--a revolutionary symbol of the French people and a subject Picasso depicted during the war years (1937-45).</p>', 20, NULL, '29', NULL, '2021-02-24 20:59:41', '2021-02-24 20:59:41'),
(55, '<blockquote><p>. شاید خیلی‌ها ندانند که نیما شعر «شهر صبح» را به عنوان دست همکاری با نهضت خروس جنگی در اختیار ما گذاشته بود و آن شعر این است؛ «قوقولی قو خروس می‌خواند/ از درون نهفت خلوت ده/ با نوایش از او ره آمد پر/ مژده می‌آورد به گوش آزاد/ می‌نماید رهش به آبادان/ کاروان را در این خراب آباد/ قوقولی قو گشاده شد دل و گوش/ صبح آمد خروس می‌خواند».</p></blockquote>', 21, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2021-02-24 23:57:35', '2021-02-24 23:57:35'),
(56, '<blockquote><p>خاطره‌ا‌‌ی جالب درباره‌ی گرفتاری‌های آن زمان به یادم آمد. در همان زمان که غوغای نقاشی کوبیسم جوانان و هنرمندان را هیجان زده کرده بود، مجله‌ی خروس جنگی توقیف شد. نیمچه محاکمه‌‌ی اداری در وزارت فرهنگ سابق تشکیل دادند و از من پرسیدند چه کسی به شما مأموریت داده کوبیسم را رواج بدهید؟ گفتم؛ خودم خواستم. خلاصه پس از پرسش‌های فراوان بالاخره پرسیدند کوبیسم یعنی چی؟ توضیح دادم شیوه نقاشی هندسی و همین قالیچه‌های زیر پایتان را کوبیسم بدانید. گفتند ما خیال می‌کردیم کوبیسم یعنی کمونیسم. خیلی عذرخواهی کردند و خواهش کردند این مطلب را به کسی نگویم. من هم نگفتم و شما هم نشنیده بگیرید</p></blockquote>', 21, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2021-02-25 00:02:46', '2021-02-25 00:02:46'),
(57, '<p>قبل از اینکه توضیحی برای شما بدهم در زمینه‌ی پرسش‌تان لازم است نکته‌ای را یادآوری کنم. شما از هنر تزیینی در برابر هنر تصویری آنچنان صحبت می‌کنید که گویی این هنر تصویری دارای محتوا و مفهوم نیست. اگر احیاناً در هنر تزیینی تصویر هم نباشد، این معنا را نخواهد داد که دارای مفهوم نیست. هنر تزیینی هم دارای تفسیر است، معانی دارد و قابل درک است و عیناً مثل هنر تصویری به ما نتیجه می‌دهد. دارای بار فرهنگی است و می‌توان درباره‌ی آن اظهار نظر کرد. ... اما از طرفی هم مردم با نقوش تزیینی ارتباط زیادی داشته‌اند. قالی، کاشی، صنایع دستی، پارچه و … همیشه در مقابل انظار مردم بوده است. مردم با نقش و نگارهای زیبا از خیلی وقت پیش آشنا بوده‌اند، پس با آن ارتباط بیشتری داشتند و به همین جهت به آنها بیشتر رو می‌آوردند. من به کلی حرف تازه‌ا‌ی می‌زدم و این برای آنها قابل قبول نبود. من ۳۰ سال جنگیدم تا بفهمانم که نقاشی بدون داشتن بینش، کاری مثل حمالی است. دوره‌ای بود که نقاشان ما گرایش ملی داشتند. عده‌ای از نقاشان هم بودند که به غرب گرایش داشتند و کار خودشان را می‌کردند. به این نقاشان‌مان می‌گفتم اهل کجا هستید؟ اگر اهل کویرید، کویری باشید و اگر شمالی هستید، شمالی باشید. کاری بکنید که مربوط به محیط خودتان باشد. حرکت‌هایی مثل سقاخانه، نقاشی قهوه‌خانه، پرده‌داری یا فرضاً خط نقاشی که در حال حاضر می‌بینیم صورت ملی دارند و از همان زمان گرایش ملی به وجود آمد و تا الان هم باقی است.</p>', 21, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2021-02-25 00:12:41', '2021-02-25 00:12:41'),
(58, '<p>یکی از مشخصات نمایش قید در این کارها است. در کارها و اطراف کاشی‌هایی که ساخته شده خطوطی مانند میله به چشم می‌خورد و به نظر می‌رسد موضوعات در پشت آن میله‌ها زندانی شده‌اند. این قیدی سرتاسری است که اجتماع روی هر فرد عادی و غیر عادی دارد. نکته‌ی دوم در این کارها سنت است. منظورم بهره‌ برداری از سنت برای یک برداشت تازه است.</p><p>در آنجا از رنگ‌آمیزی‌های سنتی استفاده کردم، منتها با برداشتی که خودم برای زمان معاصر داشتم. به دلیل اینکه فرهنگ عامه و مردم‌شناسی مدتی از موضوعات مورد مطالعه‌ام بود، کارهایم و مثلاً لباس عشایر و مردم روستایی که کار کرده‌ام از رنگ‌آمیزی‌های بسیار خوبی در اصل برخوردار بوده‌اند که من با اسلوب خودم از آنها برداشت کرده‌ام. نکته‌ی سومی که در کارم به چشم می‌خورد آزادی عمل است. هر چند قیدها برای یک هنرمند که باید آنها را رعایت کند دست و پاگیر هستند، اما آزادی عمل چیزی است که هر هنرمندی در کارش به آن نیاز دارد.</p>', 21, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2021-02-25 00:19:03', '2021-02-25 00:19:03'),
(59, '<p>خانواده‌ی من همه کفاش بودند. از ساری مازندران به گیلان مهاجرت کردند و پراکنده شدند و من در بندر انزلی پرورش یافتم. پدرم در حین انجام پیشه‌اش برای دهه‌های عزاداری از چوب مجسمه‌هایی برای مراسم تهیه می‌کرد و برای شهرستان‌ها می‌فرستاد. من هم از همان زمان‌ها با آجر و گل رسوبی مجسمه می‌ساختم. به موسیقی علاقه داشتم. در سال ۱۳۱۷ که به تهران وارد شدم برای آهنگسازی به هنرستان موسیقی رفتم، اما وقتی راهنمایی هنرستان در اختیار استاد کلنل وزیری قرار گرفت موسیقی را رها کردم و به مدرسه‌ی صنایع مستظرفه‌ی قدیمه و پس از آن هم به هنرکده رفتم.</p>', 21, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2021-02-25 00:21:40', '2021-02-25 00:21:40'),
(60, '<blockquote><p>In 1950 a group exhibition that included Ziapour at the Apadana Gallary--the first commercial gallery in Tehran--was reviewed by Jalal Al-e-Ahmad, whose anti-western book <em>Gharbzadegi </em>(westoxication), published in 1962, later became the bible of all those opposing the Pahlavi regine. Al-e Ahmad composes a Ziapour painting depicting a public bath scene to pornography but praises one depicting a mosque saying, \"it is cubist but its subject matter at least is Iranian.\" (Al-e Ahmad \"Namayeshgahe-e Naghashi dar Apadana [Paiting Exhibition at Apadana],\" Mehregan no.5. (March 7, 1950): 4)</p></blockquote>', 20, NULL, '29', NULL, '2021-02-25 01:12:43', '2021-02-25 01:12:43'),
(61, '<p>the Saqqakhaneh or \"a culturally specific modernism\"</p>', 20, NULL, '29', NULL, '2021-02-25 01:17:28', '2021-02-25 01:17:28'),
(62, '<p>In visual arts, the first major tendency to turn the gaze inward came to be known as Saqqakhaneh, a term coined by the critic Emami in 1963 to describe modernism unhampered by western crutches and rooted in local form and iconography.</p>', 20, NULL, '29', NULL, '2021-02-25 01:23:50', '2021-02-25 01:23:50'),
(63, '<p>At a time when all eyes fixed on Europe, the use of a motif such as the ubiquitous hand of Al-Abbas ibn Ali (Hazrat-e-Abbas), for instance, which was severed at the battle of Karbala in 680 CE, appeared justas avant-garde as Jasper John\'s flag, two mages that highlight, to borrow from Thomas Crow\'s writings on Johns, \"the homely exoticism of folk art.\" (Thomas Crow, <em>The Rise of the Sixties: American and European Art in the Era of Dissent, 21</em>)</p>', 20, NULL, '30', NULL, '2021-02-25 16:06:00', '2021-02-25 16:06:00'),
(64, '<p>Yaghoub Emdadian informed Daftari about Ghandriz\'s interest in Juan Miro and Paul Klee, She also mentions the School of Decorative Arts and having been born in the 1930s as common links among the participants of Saqqakhaneh, besides the use of Shi\'ite iconography.</p>', 20, NULL, 'footnote. 28. 42', NULL, '2021-02-25 16:13:40', '2021-02-25 16:13:40'),
(65, '<p>we are awash in stories.We live stories all the time.We attend to the sto- ries of others. We linger in the stories of dreams, imagination, fantasy, and memory. We</p>', 22, NULL, '1', NULL, '2021-02-25 16:24:52', '2021-02-25 16:24:52'),
(66, '<blockquote><p>...Jazeh Tabatabai (1931-2008), who began using Shi\'ite motifs but eventually diverged into an anti-military stance (his father was a member of the military) embodied in robotic sculpture, rendered as innocuous toy-like soldiers, and castrated of power.</p></blockquote>', 20, NULL, '30', NULL, '2021-02-25 16:26:18', '2021-02-25 16:26:18'),
(67, '<p>.Our stories need to be told in creative ways that hold our attention, that call out to us, that startle us, so we know our stories and the stories of others with renewed attentiveness</p>', 22, NULL, '2', NULL, '2021-02-25 16:30:31', '2021-02-25 16:30:31'),
(68, '<p>As Amis (2000) reminds us,“we live in the age of mass loquacity”(p. 6). With the unprecedented proliferation of digital literacies and social networks, such as Facebook,blogging, and YouTube,many of us live in a time and place when more and more people (at least economically privileged people) are telling more and more sto- ries about their experiences, clearly confident that their experiences deserve to be storied and shared with others, including family and friends, but also reaching out to strangers, potentially millions of unknown others.A</p>', 22, NULL, '68', NULL, '2021-02-25 20:44:40', '2021-02-25 20:44:40'),
(69, '<p>Each life is an encyclopedia, a</p><p>LEARNing library, an inventory of objects, a series of styles, and everything can be con- stantly shuffled and reordered in every way conceivable. (p. 124)</p><p>Calvino, I. (1995). Six memos for the next millen- nium.Toronto: Vintage Canada.</p>', 22, NULL, '124', NULL, '2021-02-26 13:12:23', '2021-02-26 13:12:23'),
(70, '<p>I don’t trust my stories—sentimental, sinuous, ser- pentine, full of specious spells and simulated sense.Nevertheless, I live stories and tell stories and live each day with a zany zeal for walking the line like a tightrope that stretches from one unknown to another unknown.</p>', 22, NULL, '170', NULL, '2021-02-26 13:16:35', '2021-02-26 13:16:35'),
(71, '<p>Among the earliest manifestation of interest in Shi\'ite iconography by a modern artist is <em>Who is This Hossein the World is Crazy About? </em>(first exhibited in 1960), a pre-Saqqakhaneh work by Zenderoudi reinterpreting the folk art tradition of coffeehouse painting, a genre named after one of the places they were displayed and used as props for story telling performances. Executed in linocut, a technique Zenderoudi learned in printing classes taught by fellow artist Marcos Grigorian (1927-2007), this <em>pardeh</em> (curtain), one of an edition of two, was recently acquired by the British Museum.</p>', 20, NULL, '30-31', NULL, '2021-02-26 15:39:16', '2021-02-26 15:39:16'),
(72, '<p>In Zenderoudi\'s work, some motifs are religious while others purely decorative. Streams of writing, often in a nonsensical sequence, such as <em>Tarzan</em> next to <em>aftabeh </em>(toilet water ewer), next to <em>ash-e reshteh </em>(a dish), or a text taken from children\'s game (<em>kalagh par, gav par...</em>), create a vernacular neither sacred nor literary, but highly populist, humorous, and juvenile in nature. The cryptic and the humorous mingle in this early work to reveal the artist as an esoteric prankster. [in reference to a 13-meter scroll of pasted pepper exhibited only once, in 1961, at the Atelier Kaboud]</p>', 20, NULL, '32', NULL, '2021-02-26 15:48:07', '2021-02-26 15:48:07'),
(73, '<blockquote><p>It is, however, Zenderoudi\'s elevation of humble media (pen on wrapping paper), and the turning of his gaze toward non-art-museum objects, ignored or disdained by the westernized elite during a markedly secular period of Iranian history, that was groundbreaking.</p></blockquote><p>Daftari argues that Zenderoudi\'s blurring the boundaries b/w decorative art and fine art is groundbreaking and protests against the elitism of the western canon. What she, however, leaves out the Iranian elites had already started to collect popular and decorative objects, including Qajar reversed-glass painting, coffee house paintings. It seems that the class politics of the desire for decorative art in the 1960s is more complex as an easy anti-western stance rhetoric.</p>', 20, NULL, '32', NULL, '2021-02-26 16:03:25', '2021-02-26 16:03:25'),
(74, '<p>Zenderoudi\'s <em>K+L+32+H+4: Mom pere et moi </em>(me and my father) (1962), acquired by Alfred H. Barr, Jr. from the Venice Biennale for The Museum of Modern Art, dates from the same year as Andy Warhol\'s <em>Soup Cans.</em> Yet Zenderoudi\'s version of pop does not embrace commercial products. It is cryptically religious.  </p>', 20, NULL, '32', NULL, '2021-02-26 16:23:09', '2021-02-26 16:23:09'),
(75, '<blockquote><p>[In <em>The Sun &amp; The Lion</em>]...the figure of a stylized lion juxtaposed over a solar background emerges from the minute system of mark-making (numerology, writing, and geometric patterns). Traditionally, the sun and the lion have stood as the emblem of the monarchy, but Zenderoudi invests them with religious meaning: the standard held by the lion is a reference to the <em>zolfaghar, </em>Ali ibn Ali Talib\'s two-pronged sword. These two works on paper were acquired by Mrs Abby Weed Grey who had formed her collection of Iranian art...when traveling in the region from 1960 to 1973.</p></blockquote><p>Here, Daftari dismisses the prank that Zenderoudi pulls by referencing an eroticized lion, the intricate inscriptions form a complex web of desire. </p>', 20, NULL, '32', NULL, '2021-02-26 16:33:40', '2021-02-26 16:33:40'),
(76, '<blockquote><p>The French critic <a href=\"https://www.google.com/url?sa=i&amp;url=https%3A%2F%2Fsammlung.staedelmuseum.de%2Fen%2Fwork%2Fmichel-tapie-grand-duc&amp;psig=AOvVaw1N7PnMovmdssMA1kP6NxOE&amp;ust=1614444000491000&amp;source=images&amp;cd=vfe&amp;ved=2ahUKEwjtq8Xa_ofvAhUbFc0KHTLNBE0Qjhx6BAgAEBI\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\">Michel Tapié</a>, whose interest i Art Autre led him to promote the Japanese Gautai group and the Iranians in Europe, introduced Zenederoudi to the Stadler Gallery, where the Lettristes were exhibiting (in the 1970s <a href=\"https://www.google.com/url?sa=i&amp;url=https%3A%2F%2Fsammlung.staedelmuseum.de%2Fen%2Fwork%2Fmichel-tapie-grand-duc&amp;psig=AOvVaw1N7PnMovmdssMA1kP6NxOE&amp;ust=1614444000491000&amp;source=images&amp;cd=vfe&amp;ved=2ahUKEwjtq8Xa_ofvAhUbFc0KHTLNBE0Qjhx6BAgAEBI\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\">Tapié</a> directed the Galarie Cyrus at the Maison del\'Iran in Paris).</p></blockquote>', 20, NULL, '32', NULL, '2021-02-26 17:06:56', '2021-02-26 17:06:56'),
(77, '<blockquote><p>Zenderoudi met Isidore Isou and attended some of the Lettristes\' meetings in cafes but withdrew from their company citing their \"Dadaist and nihist tendencies\" Pierre Restany, quoting Pierre Cabanne, indicates that Zenderoudi\'s work is characterized by <em>un lettrisme sacr</em>é<em> </em>(sacred lettrism). in some of his playful uses of language, however, Zenderoudi does reveal a Dadaist side he has both manifested and downplayed.</p></blockquote>', 20, NULL, '33', NULL, '2021-02-26 17:43:41', '2021-02-26 17:43:41'),
(78, '<blockquote><p>More importantly \"calligraphic modernism,\" as Iftikhar Dadi has named the practice, especially when it migrated from paper to canvas, was a widespread phenomenon found in the entire region beyond Iran. Neda Shabout has traced the discourse surrounding the development of the Arabic script from traditional calligraphy of the Islamic age to modern Hurufiyya for the Arabic world, and Dadi has framed it as a pan-Islamist aesthetic. in Iran, or even in dispora (Zenderoudi has lived in France since 1961), this calligraphic modernism, complex and diverse in its references, at times incorporates irreverent text in sloppy handwriting antithetical to a pan-islamic impulse, or asserts an identity that is secular and Iranian, not to be misconstrued as Arabic and Islamic. In Iran the trend ran parallel to the more traditional approach by classically trained calligraphers such as Reza Mafi and Mohammad Ehsai...</p></blockquote>', 20, NULL, '33', NULL, '2021-02-26 18:26:38', '2021-02-26 18:26:38'),
(79, '<blockquote><p>In Minneapolis he [Tanavoli] combined the anthropocentrism of western sculpture with the banal vocabulary of ordinary such as locks and tubes to creat sculptures such as the <em>Bronze Prophet</em>--perhaps a metaphor for a developing nation that is materially hampered but spiritually proud.</p></blockquote>', 20, NULL, '33', NULL, '2021-02-26 18:33:10', '2021-02-26 18:33:10'),
(80, '<blockquote><p><em>Innovation in Art, a </em>mixed media work with a sardonic title, gives an iconic centrality to a lavatory ewer, a humble object, transgressively irreverent. Tanavoli covered the ewer with paint and placed it at the heart of a made-in-Kashan medallion rug turned into a prayer rug, just below a sash of pumpkin seeds; ...It may be seen as a critique of homemade art parading as innovation and is perhaps a critique of homemade art parading as innovation and is perhaps a critique of the culture feeding the Saqqakhaneh iconography. This work was paired with a mechanized lavatory (1964), satirizing Iran\'s industrial progress.</p></blockquote>', 20, NULL, '33', NULL, '2021-02-26 20:06:53', '2021-02-26 20:06:53'),
(81, '<p>Fluidly they morphed into an interval vocabulary as in <em>Confrontation, </em>where the cryptic signs recalling heiroglyphs suggest, according to a label in Perisan found on the work, \"the poet and the miracle of the cane.\" To prove the higher authority of God over pharaoh, Moses performs a miracle by striking his staff to the ground and turning it into a serpent; once again we see a conflation of poet and prophet, both of whom the artist identified with.</p>', 20, NULL, '34', NULL, '2021-02-26 20:23:13', '2021-02-26 20:23:13'),
(82, '<p>While a/r/tography is inherently about self, it is also about communities of a/r/tographers working together in shared inquiry, articulating an evolution of research questions and performing evocative and/or provocative works for others. In this way, one condition of a/r/tography is that relational aesthetic inquiry guides the exchanges between and among text and art, as well as practice and theory. How these relational forms of inquiry are rendered is found in the conceptual under- pinnings of the work</p>', 23, NULL, '240', NULL, '2021-02-27 05:12:08', '2021-02-27 05:12:08'),
(83, '<p>Living inquiry can be effectively pursued through life writing by exploring experiences that are personal, political, and professional through memory, autobiography, reflection, storying, interpretation, and more (Springgay, Irwin, and Kind 2005).</p>', 23, NULL, '241', NULL, '2021-02-27 05:16:20', '2021-02-27 05:16:20'),
(84, '<p> Living inquiry is transformative, rooted in emotions, and to borrow Kusenbach’s concept of emotional markers, depends on emotions as ‘entry points for the researcher to recollect and relive field experiences during analysis’, which can generate alternate ways of rendering the research experience (Kusenbach 2002, 150). </p>', 22, NULL, '245', NULL, '2021-02-27 13:16:23', '2021-02-27 13:16:23'),
(85, '<p>Clifford (1986) explains them: ‘The predominant metaphors in anthropological research have been participant-observation, data collection, and cultural description, all of which presuppose a standpoint outside – looking at, objectifying, or, somewhat closer, ‘reading’, a given reality’ (11). 245</p>', 23, NULL, '245', NULL, '2021-02-27 13:22:35', '2021-02-27 13:22:35'),
(86, '<p>Ethnography and a/r/tography are both naturalistic approaches, but ethnographers are ‘more likely to analyze the interrelations between publicly observable rituals, symbols, and concepts’, whereas artists ‘describe what they experience’ and, ‘create virtual experiences in language, space, time, or sound so that others can grasp what they perceive directly, through encountering a new work of art’ (Alexander 2003, 3). The arts focus on the expression and evocation of perceptions and feelings. A/r/tographic research, such as arts practice-based research in general, ‘enables an outsider to view an event from the inside’, resulting in a ‘reeducation of perception’ (Alexander 2003, 5–6)</p>', 23, NULL, '245', NULL, '2021-02-27 14:30:55', '2021-02-27 14:30:55'),
(87, '<p>In <em>On Persepolis </em>of 1975, where the invented ideogram parody the bas-reliefs on the Apadana staircase in Persepolis, representing dignitaries who had come from the twenty-three nations of the empire to pay homage to the Achaemenid king, and perhaps the military processions familiar to modern Iranians, the reference may be to narratives of power, to tablets and lofty edicts delivered by visionary autocrats. The \"Oh\" in the title may be more just an expression of awe or nostalgia for an ancient civilization. It also betrays sarcasm, perhaps hinting at recent event in Persepolis, which in 1971 had been the site of controversial celebrations. Tanavoli appears to converse in the dialectics of power with the subversive intention of denouncing and not glorifying the ideologies sustaining those powers.</p>', 20, NULL, '34', NULL, '2021-02-27 17:56:48', '2021-02-27 17:56:48'),
(88, '<blockquote><p>No single characterization can sum up the modernism created by Iranian artists before the revolution. ... In its pluralism their work derives from a desire to be rooted while open to exploration, and ranges from the culturally specific to the cosmopolitan, from the purely abstract to the manifestly political, from classism to Pop and conceptualism, from revisions of traditional iconography to the embrace of popular culture, from appropriation to invention, and expresses a hybridity that embraces many these options. Today cross-cultural references, unplagued by stigma, are embraced around the globe. The Iranian modernists paved the way. </p></blockquote>', 20, NULL, '40', NULL, '2021-02-27 20:47:05', '2021-02-27 20:47:05'),
(89, '<blockquote><p>It may be time to cast a fresh look at individuals who have contributed a chapter to the global discourse on difference and who invented their own modernism one sensibility at a time.</p></blockquote>', 20, NULL, '41', NULL, '2021-02-28 17:27:19', '2021-02-28 17:27:19'),
(90, '<p>The artist says the works \"were influenced by a mixture of Persian miniatures and Persian folk fairytales and by what I observed in the neighborhoods in South Tehran--such sights as scribes stationed in front of the Central Post Office writing letters on behalf of illiterates. Many, however, present language deconstructed into his sculptures of architectural models, which he named \"Dictionary for Building.\" </p>', 20, NULL, '39', NULL, '2021-02-28 17:35:57', '2021-02-28 17:35:57'),
(91, '<p>An activist--initially with Marxism then in Mosaddegh\'s National Front movement--Siah ARmajani left Iran in 1960, at the age of twenty-one, for the Twin Cities in Minnnesota.</p>', 20, NULL, '39', NULL, '2021-02-28 17:38:46', '2021-02-28 17:38:46'),
(92, '<blockquote><p>His art is filtered through the dusty hue of the desert and the lessons he learned from Far Eastern art during a printmaking apprenticeship in Tokyo (August 1960-March 1961). The subdued Zen culture and minimalist aesthetics resonated with this painter who was above all a poet of distilled simplicity.</p></blockquote>', 20, NULL, '38', NULL, '2021-02-28 17:47:20', '2021-02-28 17:47:20'),
(93, '<blockquote><p>Zenderoudi may be indebted to Grigorian not just for the linocut technique he learned from him, but also for the choice of his coffeehouse inspired <em>pardeh.</em></p></blockquote>', 20, NULL, '37', NULL, '2021-02-28 17:52:06', '2021-02-28 17:52:06'),
(94, '<blockquote><p>Grigorian was of Armenian descent. His nomadic trajectory took him from his birthpalce, in Kroptkin, Russia, to Tabriz at the age of five, then to Tehran, Rome, Minneapolis, New York and his final resting place in Yervan, Armenia. In addition to being known as Armenian, Iranian, and American, he also identified himself as Italian. Grigorian was a global artist before the term was coined.</p></blockquote>', 20, NULL, '36', NULL, '2021-02-28 17:56:41', '2021-02-28 17:56:41'),
(95, '<p>Thus the origin of her abstraction is not to be found in New York, as posited by her friend the artist Frank Stella, but rather in Shiraz in the mesmerizing mirror works that dissolve into light.</p>', 20, NULL, '36', NULL, '2021-02-28 18:00:43', '2021-02-28 18:00:43'),
(96, '<p>Karim Emami hailed [<em>Khorous Jangi</em>] the journal as the \"unofficial battle cry of modernism.\"</p>', 24, NULL, '45', NULL, '2021-02-28 18:25:41', '2021-02-28 18:25:41'),
(97, '<p>Diba argues that \"high\" and \"low\" coexisted and at times equivalent in Iranian culture. She also argue that with the invention of modernism in Iran, one can identify the invention of tradition.</p>', 24, NULL, '45', NULL, '2021-02-28 18:30:11', '2021-02-28 18:30:11'),
(98, '<p>Cultural power was vested in the Ministry of Education and in the Office of Fine Arts, which was established in 1950 and elevated to a ministry in 1964. From the 1950s onward, these newly expanded and empowered ministries were assigned increased responsibilities for education and the arts. ...The Higher Council for the Arts, established in 1967, developed policy and oversaw its implementation. The Council\'s dictatorship comprised the Minister of Art, representatives of government organizations, and even artists.</p>', 24, NULL, '53', NULL, '2021-02-28 19:16:00', '2021-02-28 19:16:00');
INSERT INTO `codes` (`id`, `body`, `reference_id`, `notes`, `pages`, `deleted_at`, `created_at`, `updated_at`) VALUES
(99, '<p>In 1959 the office of Queen Farah Pahlavi was established after her marriage to the Shah. ... Her support of art and culture was broad-based and encompassed traditional as well as contemporary Iranian and international art, Iranian handicrafts, and the preservation of historic Iranian monuments. Eventually the Queen and her art advisor became a kind of shadow ministry.</p>', 24, NULL, '53', NULL, '2021-02-28 19:52:57', '2021-02-28 19:52:57'),
(100, '<p>The Department of Fine Arts, and later the Ministry, initially encouraged the traditional arts. By way of example, Ali Karimi, champion of revival-style art and a close associate of Mehrdad Pahlbod, the Minister of Art, and director of Madreseh was appointed not only to high government position such as Fine Arts Inspector but also to modern art exhibition juries, where he represented the conservative government aganda.</p>', 24, NULL, '53', NULL, '2021-02-28 20:36:10', '2021-02-28 20:36:10'),
(101, '<p>The late 1940s also witnessed the beginning of an audience for art. Group exhibitions of Iranian modern art were presented at Russian cultural society VOKS in the 1946 and at the Mehregan Club of the local Iranian Teachers Association in the early 1950s. Although the academic style predominated, revivalists and modernists were also represented, possibly reflecting the political pluralism of the late 1940s and the early 1950s.</p>', 24, NULL, '54', NULL, '2021-02-28 20:47:41', '2021-02-28 20:47:41'),
(102, '<p>His career exemplifies an alternative approach to the Paris School of abstract modernism. From 1942 to 1948, Pezeshknia, like Hossein Zaherzadeh before him, studied in Istanbul, where he became familiar not only with the work of Leopold Levy, a French academic teaching at the Fine Art Academy of Istanbul but also with various forms of European expressionism. </p><p>On his return to Iran, Pezeshknia turned to teaching in order to supplement the income from his artistic activities, and he embarked on a career as a government bureaucrat and employee of the Anglo-Iranian oil company in Abadan from 1948 to 1958.</p>', 24, NULL, '54', NULL, '2021-03-01 00:01:59', '2021-03-01 00:01:59'),
(103, '<p>Andre Lhote welcomed foreign students and his influence spread as far as India and Australia. [see Iftikhar Dadi, <em>Modernism and the Art of Muslim South Asia</em>]</p>', 24, NULL, '63', NULL, '2021-03-01 00:39:05', '2021-03-01 00:39:05'),
(104, '<p>Tanavoli further transformed teaching at the Faculty when in 1969 he established a foundry for his sculpture classes, which was funded by the American philanthropist Abby Weed Grey.</p>', 24, NULL, '54', NULL, '2021-03-01 00:41:45', '2021-03-01 00:41:45'),
(105, '<p>Beginning in 1958, a series of five biennials were organized under the direction of the Ministry of Culture through the agency of the Armenian-Iranian artist Marcos Grigorian (1925-2007).</p>', 24, NULL, '54-55', NULL, '2021-03-01 00:48:25', '2021-03-01 00:48:25'),
(106, '<p>The year 1962 witnesses the birth of the Saqqakhaneh school (local modernism combining popular culture, text, and abstraction) at the Third Biennial and almost simultaneously <em>Naqqashi-Khat,</em> a movement toward calligraphy in art, as some source also, claim.</p>', 24, NULL, '55', NULL, '2021-03-01 00:53:31', '2021-03-01 00:53:31'),
(107, '<p>Rockefeller, along with Henry Kissinger attended the openning of TMoCA in October 1977. </p>', 24, NULL, 'fn.90 64', NULL, '2021-03-01 01:00:20', '2021-03-01 01:00:20'),
(108, '<p>Rockefeller acquired Grigorian\'s works for his own collection. [<em>The Nelson A. Rockefeller Collection, 214</em>] The group of Iranian modern artwork that the Museum acquired in the 1960s, in addition to Grigorian included works by Pilaram, Zenderoudi, Tanavoli, and Vaziri-Moqaddam. Tanavoli helpred Grey form her impressive modern Iranian art collection, which is now housed at New York University and id the only major public collection outside Iran.</p>', 24, NULL, '91', NULL, '2021-03-01 01:09:05', '2021-03-01 01:09:05'),
(109, '<p>The Queen and her advisors became a locus for innovative ideas, which spurred the surge of local modernism.</p>', 24, NULL, '55', NULL, '2021-03-01 01:17:54', '2021-03-01 01:17:54'),
(110, '<p>...in the retrospect the Festival\'s revival of the Persian Passion Play devoted to the tragedy of Karbala, known as <em>Ta\'zeih,</em> and the government support of avant-garde theater and performance art, encouraged Iranian artist to be adventurous and to search for new ideas and nontraditional art forms.</p>', 24, NULL, 'fn. 92 64', NULL, '2021-03-01 01:24:19', '2021-03-01 01:24:19'),
(111, '<p>Arts patrons supported both Safavid revival and modern art. The Ministry of Culture supported conservative trends, while the Queen encouraged the avant-garde. `</p>', 24, NULL, '55', NULL, '2021-03-01 01:30:30', '2021-03-01 01:30:30'),
(112, '<p><br>“as a classroom community, our capacity to generate excitement is deeply affected by our interest in one another, in hearing one another’s voices, in recognizing one another’s presence” (p. 8) and “when eros is present in the classroom setting, then love is bound to flourish. [Yet] well-learned distinctions between public and private make us believe that love has no place in the classroom” (p. 198). Let’s</p><h3></h3>', 25, NULL, '198', NULL, '2021-03-01 18:03:01', '2021-03-01 18:03:01'),
(113, '<p>I’m suggesting that when the inloveness of educational eros is acknowledged in the dialogic space between teacher and learner, transformational knowing possibilities are greatly enhanced. So I’m thinking about learning as related- ness, learning as eros, and learning as love.</p>', 26, NULL, '64', NULL, '2021-03-01 18:25:41', '2021-03-01 18:25:41'),
(114, '<p>Motivated by Frederick Franck’s (1993) commitment “to live in radical openness to pure experiencing in kitchen, bedroom, subway, newspaper, that is: to everyday life, inside as well as around oneself” (p. 10), I live, as our friend Celeste Snowber reminds us, in “the erotics of the everyday” (personal communication, October 4, 1996)</p>', 26, NULL, '67', NULL, '2021-03-01 18:39:33', '2021-03-01 18:39:33'),
(115, '<p>The challenge in writing and living love stories is to acknowledge that some stories are lived on paper, some in imagination, some in dreams, some in the quintessential quotidian quotient of each day’s daily extra-ordinariness.</p>', 26, NULL, '67', NULL, '2021-03-01 18:41:34', '2021-03-01 18:41:34'),
(116, '<p>McLaren’s (1991) advice that “a politics of field relations must be grounded in eros, in passion, in commitment to transform through a radical connectedness to the self and the other” (p. 163)?</p>', 26, NULL, '67', NULL, '2021-03-01 18:51:23', '2021-03-01 18:51:23'),
(117, '<p>Relating—making desire embodied, is an integral but wholesomely necessary part of learn-</p><p>ing in love. Learning in eros is erotic—it is a deep connection between learners which involves insertion, vulnerability, and a courageous commitment to entanglement.</p>', 26, NULL, '71', NULL, '2021-03-01 20:34:58', '2021-03-01 20:34:58'),
(118, '<p>Hélène Cixous (1993) recommends that “perhaps going in the</p><p>direction of what we call truth is, at least, to ‘unlie,’ not to lie. Our lives are buildings made up of</p><p>lies. We have to lie to live. But to write we must try to unlie” (p. 36).</p>', 26, NULL, '71', NULL, '2021-03-01 20:40:36', '2021-03-01 20:40:36'),
(119, '<p>Your comment on being “intent in the instant” is well described by Mitchell Thomashow</p><p>(1995). Much like the inloveness space of eros, being attuned to the everyday experience be-tween teacher and learner, body and context, and inside and outside, enables the realization that</p><p>“it is the process of thinking about the question that guides [the] experience” (p. 202).</p>', 26, NULL, '74', NULL, '2021-03-01 21:01:14', '2021-03-01 21:01:14'),
(120, '<p>I wonder, in our contemporary classrooms, how we can foster a sustainable stillness, a deep contemplation and a movement toward wisdom when our society is moving about so quickly with quick fixes and unconnected learning in disparate classes</p>', 26, NULL, '74', NULL, '2021-03-01 21:03:34', '2021-03-01 21:03:34'),
(121, '<p>Otto Bollnow’s (1989b) description of educational love, which embraces patience,</p><p>hope, serenity, humour, and goodness. Bollnow (1989a) says that a pedagogic trust relationship</p><p>creates a sense of “morningness” (p. 22). Morningness refers to newness or a sense of budding</p><p>joy for learning.</p>', 26, NULL, '75', NULL, '2021-03-01 21:05:32', '2021-03-01 21:05:32'),
(122, '<p>In All About Love: New Visions, bell hooks (2000) acknowledges how difficult it is to talk</p><p>about the heart: “Taught to believe that the mind, not the heart, is the seat of learning, many of us believe that to speak of love with any emotional intensity means we will be perceived as weak and irrational” (p. xxvii). Hooks understands that “to open our hearts more fully to love’s power and grace we must dare to acknowledge how little we know of love in both theory and practice” p. xxix). Even though we are constantly living by heart, learning by heart, attending to the heart, we still know little about love, little about the experience of the heart.</p>', 26, NULL, '76', NULL, '2021-03-01 21:11:08', '2021-03-01 21:11:08'),
(123, '<p>As we look back on the last half of the twentieth century, it seems clear that culture moved to the foreground. It is not, to be sure, that there had been no culture before 1950, but it was always in a period\'s background. ...But suddenly, in the age of three worlds, everyone discovered that culture and culture had a mass.</p>', 27, NULL, '1', NULL, '2021-03-01 22:34:16', '2021-03-01 22:34:16'),
(124, '<p>The global cultural turn was a consequence of the uneven development of a global culture out of the cultural and ideological struggles between the three worlds. </p>', 27, NULL, '2', NULL, '2021-03-01 22:47:41', '2021-03-01 22:47:41'),
(125, '<p>Denning considers mass media and decolonialization the grounds for the cultural turn:</p><blockquote><p>The differentionation of the cultural studies in the age of three world was, I will suggest, the resut of the emergence of yet another aspect of social reality--the culture industries, the mass media, mass communications--which seemed to have its own autonomy, its own logic, ad its own power. ...Thus the study of the logic od this new world, the logic of mass communication, the logic of culture in a new sense, became the fifth social science, a postmodern social science, linked, as we shall see, to that other reorganization of the social sciences in the age of three worlds: area studies.  But the cultural turn was never simply this academic tropism toward the light and heat of the mass media. FRom the start, it was also a moment of reneweal and renovation in radical and socialist thought, generated from the crisis of Stalinism, from the contradications of what was seen as a new form of capitalist society, and from the victories of decolonialization.</p></blockquote>', 27, NULL, '5', NULL, '2021-03-01 23:23:08', '2021-03-01 23:23:08'),
(126, '<p>For a generation of New Left thinkers around the globe, the issue of culture was not simply the fact of the existence of the new technologies of mass information and communication, but the reshaping of the everyday lives and struggles of subaltern classes and peoples by those new forms. If the modernist notions culture named those social sites where the commodity form and its law of value did not yet rule--the high arts, on the one hand, and the lifeways of \'primitive\' peoples, on the other--the new postmodern concept of culture was premised on the generalization of the commodity form, not only in symbolic production but throughout daily life. ...the New Left thinkers made culture and its cognates the vehicle for a reconsideration of the very processes of social maintenance and reproduction under capitalism.</p>', 27, NULL, '5-6', NULL, '2021-03-01 23:48:45', '2021-03-01 23:48:45'),
(127, '<p>The debate over the status and efficacy of culture as a site and form of political resistance, of the relation between culture and social movements, echoed across the age of three worlds and beyond; </p>', 27, NULL, '6', NULL, '2021-03-02 00:06:56', '2021-03-02 00:06:56'),
(128, '<p>Finally, the cultural turn marked New Left in all three worlds.</p>', 27, NULL, '6', NULL, '2021-03-02 00:09:14', '2021-03-02 00:09:14'),
(129, '<p>But the cultural turn was also due to the globalization effect of the Communist experience: the post-1917 generation steeped in the cauldron of Leninist militancy, Popular Front anti-fascism, and a revolutionary anticolonialism. If the genuinely internationalist ideology of the Communist movement nurtured the remarkable spread of anti-imperialist solidarities, its equally vigorous Soviet loyalism reproduced the rigidities of Cofmitern Marxism on every continent. One of the central rigidities was the economism of Communist Marxism, its discounting of culture--merely a superstructure--and of national and regional particularities.</p>', 27, NULL, '7', NULL, '2021-03-02 00:36:22', '2021-03-02 00:36:22'),
(130, '<p>It is not that these figures influenced each other; in fact, precisely because the cultural turn was usually a turn to what Gramsci had called the \"national-popular\"--the regional and national particularities often ignore by the abstract internationalism of Comintern Marxism--explicit cross-national theories and debate about culture did not develop.</p>', 27, NULL, '8', NULL, '2021-03-02 00:43:01', '2021-03-02 00:43:01'),
(131, '<p>It is perhaps not surprising that many of the central figures of this contemporary transnational cultural controversy over alternative modernities--a  name in part for the age of three worlds, now seen as the era of nation-focused modernization and development from whose success or failure one is now escaping--and their hybrid subjects were formed intellectually in the earlier moment\'s reckoning with the crisis of the popular in particular national situations.</p>', 27, NULL, '9', NULL, '2021-03-02 01:45:01', '2021-03-02 01:45:01'),
(132, '<p>Arguing that the effort to create a proletarian culture in the early decades of the century was a fundamental part of the globalization of the novel, it suggests that what we inherit as a global culture is not simply an emporium of commodities marked around the world, but a powerful body of narratives that emerged out of the clash of the three worlds.</p>', 27, NULL, '12', NULL, '2021-03-02 14:43:59', '2021-03-02 14:43:59'),
(133, '<blockquote><p>Visceral rhythms are the driving force of feeding behavior, while smell, taste and touch are the agent of perception. Affective behavior is determined by perception of the play of the muscles as well as by touch, smell, and sight. Behavior pertaining to one\'s position in space and time is served by the organs of balance, and perception of the body in space is determined by reference to the dominant sense, which i the human is the sense of vision and in other species the senses of smell, touch, or hearing. none of the three levels of relationship with the external environment is conceivable without a certain rhythmicity of the body and without a reference mechanism.</p></blockquote>', 28, NULL, '282', NULL, '2021-03-02 22:02:38', '2021-03-02 22:02:38'),
(134, '<p>I do not expect an answer to a problem when I read a poem; but</p><p>I hope to find a new way of looking at something that I have been staring at</p><p>for a long time. Poet and essayist Adrienne Rich writes: “Take that old,</p><p>material utensil, language, found all about you, blank with familiarity,</p><p>smeared with daily use, and make it into something that means more than</p><p>it says” (ibid.).</p>', 29, NULL, '76', NULL, '2021-03-02 22:05:34', '2021-03-02 22:05:34'),
(135, '<p>We would do well to approach a body of theoretical literature as</p><p>if we were approaching a collection of poems—sifting through both for</p><p>meaning and clarity, sometimes hope; not rushing to conclusions; waiting</p><p>patiently for an image,metaphor, or example to resonate with us; and “being</p><p>alert and ready for unaccountable beauty, for the intricateness or simple</p><p>elegance of the writer’s imagination, for the world that imagination evokes”</p><p>(Morrison, 1992, xi).</p>', 29, NULL, '76', NULL, '2021-03-02 22:09:56', '2021-03-02 22:09:56'),
(136, '<p>According to John Wylie (2005), a</p><p>walk in the English countryside “involves at least some attunement with the var-ious sensibilities still distilling from sublime and romantic figurations of the self,</p><p>travel, landscape and nature” (235).</p>', 31, NULL, '61', NULL, '2021-03-07 00:58:21', '2021-03-07 00:58:21'),
(137, '<p>. Erin Manning (2013) discusses how propositions are immanent to events and co-constitutive. F</p>', 31, NULL, '64', NULL, '2021-03-07 01:35:09', '2021-03-07 01:35:09'),
(138, '<p>Affect has been theorized from within a variety of academic lineages (Seigworth and Gregg 2010). We understand affect within our research-creation practice as “the becoming sensation, a force or intensity manifested at the surface of the body” (Springgay and Zaliwska 2017, 276-277), “found in those intensities that pass body to body ... in those resonances that circulate about, between” (Sei- gworth and Gregg 2010, 1), felt-or-not, capacitating and debilitating further affectivity (Massumi 2015; Puar 2017)</p>', 31, NULL, '62', NULL, '2021-03-07 01:43:48', '2021-03-07 01:43:48'),
(139, '<p>“shared concern for nonconscious, non-cognitive, transcorporeal, and non-representational processes” (Springgay and Truman 2017, 11).</p>', 31, NULL, '63', NULL, '2021-03-07 12:55:27', '2021-03-07 12:55:27'),
(140, '<p>In reference to one of the original prompts of the project: in what ways would walking a long distance help our composition process; our practice of walk- ing-composing appears to support claims that walking can lead to inspiration, under the right circumstances. W</p>', 31, NULL, '69', NULL, '2021-03-08 12:13:26', '2021-03-08 12:13:26'),
(141, '<p>Artists have been called to join the research endeavor and are empowered to create artistic works with recognition of the scholarship embodied in what Richardson (2000) calls Creative Analytical Practices.</p><p>In response to this call,</p><p>artists are seeking ways to think of themselves as researchers, just as researchers are repositioning their identities as artists (Bickel, 2005). Through</p>', 32, NULL, '4', NULL, '2021-03-08 12:30:58', '2021-03-08 12:30:58'),
(142, '<p>A/r/tography is seen as a form of lived practice-based inquiry (Irwin &amp; Springgay, 2008; Sinner, Irwin, Leggo, Gouzouasis, &amp; Grauer, 2006; Springgay, Irwin, Leggo &amp; Gouzouasis, 2008)</p>', 23, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2021-03-08 12:33:12', '2021-03-08 12:33:12'),
(143, '<p>Inquiries are formed as a questioning, a curiosity, a troubling, which ask us to “live the questions” as Rilke directed his young poet to do (1903/1986, p. 34-35). The term “inquiry” provides for embodied open-ended research processes.</p>', 32, NULL, '4', NULL, '2021-03-08 12:34:53', '2021-03-08 12:34:53'),
(144, '<p>Inquiry does not assume a simple question to which we are finding a simple answer, but allows multiple, complicated, simultaneous, and even contradictory viewpoints to be held. “The</p>', 32, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2021-03-08 12:36:22', '2021-03-08 12:36:22'),
(145, '<p>The action is the knowing, and the knowing informs the action. </p>', 32, NULL, '6', NULL, '2021-03-08 14:33:28', '2021-03-08 14:33:28'),
(146, '<p>The music makes sense of the music. Echoing the organizational form of a musical fugue, Gouzouasis and Lee (2002) use narrative, poetry, exposition and dialogue to point to the resonance of music as a means for getting at “the truth.” Gouzouasis writes: “I always find truth in music.…Whether in music composition, music improvisation, music listening, or music performance; whether I’m working solo or in a group, music has always provided me with truthful insights” (p. 135)</p>', 32, NULL, '7', NULL, '2021-03-08 14:44:02', '2021-03-08 14:44:02'),
(147, '<p>A/r/tography focuses on the connected spaces in-between these roles and the communities of practice in which they emerge (Irwin &amp; Springgay, 2008; Irwin, 2008; Springgay, Irwin, Kind, 2008; Wenger, 2006)</p>', 32, NULL, '67', NULL, '2021-03-08 21:18:34', '2021-03-08 21:18:34'),
(148, '<p> Knowledge is understood as unfolding in a participatory discovery process. The teacher is not separate from their students. </p>', 32, NULL, '67', NULL, '2021-03-08 21:19:42', '2021-03-08 21:19:42'),
(149, '<p>Hermeneutics pays attention to the silences and the spaces in between the known and the knower. </p>', 32, NULL, '13', NULL, '2021-03-08 21:27:31', '2021-03-08 21:27:31'),
(150, '<p>“… the future and past only exist (really exist) in stories. Neither is real. The future isn’t here yet so isn’t real, and the past is gone and so it’s not real (anymore) either” (Larson, 2011)</p>', 32, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2021-03-08 22:01:54', '2021-03-08 22:01:54'),
(151, '<p></p><p>“Stories are the glue Larson, 2011, p. 17. that joins the future with the past through the present”</p><p></p>', 32, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2021-03-08 22:16:40', '2021-03-08 22:16:40'),
(152, '<p>Paul Klee had explicit resort to this comparison in his celebrated definition of drawing as ‘taking a line for a walk’.1 Subsequently,</p>', 33, NULL, '60', NULL, '2021-03-09 14:02:03', '2021-03-09 14:02:03'),
(153, '<p>There are, nevertheless, important differences between walking and drawing which complicate the idea of path-making as a simple process of inscribing the ground.</p>', 33, NULL, '60', NULL, '2021-03-09 14:03:13', '2021-03-09 14:03:13'),
(154, '<p>Walking, in this regard, is much like talking, and both are quintessential features of what we take to be a human form of life. We are already talking by the time we realize that this is what we are doing; and only those who remain after we are gone will know which words will have been our last. So it is, too, with our first and last steps. Life itself is as much a long walk as it is a long conversation, and the ways along which we walk are those along which we live.</p>', 34, NULL, '1', NULL, '2021-03-09 14:39:00', '2021-03-09 14:39:00'),
(155, '<p>(Bourdieu 1977, 87). A way of walking, for example, does not merely express thoughts and feelings that have already been imparted through an education in cultural precepts and proprieties. It is itself a way of thinking and of feeling, through which, in the practice of pedestrian movement, these cultural forms are continually generated (ibid., 93-4</p>', 34, NULL, '2', NULL, '2021-03-09 14:41:03', '2021-03-09 14:41:03'),
(156, '<p>through our feet, in contact with the ground (albeit mediated by footwear), that we are most fundamentally and continually ‘in touch’ with our surroundings.11 Of</p>', 35, NULL, '330', NULL, '2021-03-09 15:06:39', '2021-03-09 15:06:39'),
(157, '<p>Since the other was hesitated to recognize me, there remained only one condition: to make myself known.</p>', 36, NULL, '115', NULL, '2021-03-09 18:43:54', '2021-03-09 18:43:54'),
(158, '<p>The psychoanalysts say that nothing is more traumatizing for the young child than his encounters with what is rational. I would personally say that for a man whose only weapon is reason there is nothing more neuritic than contact with unreason.</p>', 36, NULL, '118', NULL, '2021-03-09 19:00:26', '2021-03-09 19:00:26'),
(159, '<p>here I am at home; I am made of irrational; I wade in the irrational. Up to the neck in the irrational.</p>', 36, NULL, '123', NULL, '2021-03-09 19:19:14', '2021-03-09 19:19:14'),
(160, '<p>The aesthetic experience - in its limited sense-- is thus seen to be inherently connected with the experience of making</p>', 6, NULL, '49', NULL, '2021-03-11 17:12:05', '2021-03-11 17:12:05'),
(161, '<blockquote><p>Contrasting the French experience to the slow, steady, \"rational\" modernization of American society that transpired throughout the twentieth century, Lefebvre evoked the almost cargo-cult-like, sudden descent of large appliances into war-torn French households and streets in the wake of the Marshall Plan.</p></blockquote>', 38, NULL, '4', NULL, '2021-03-12 21:39:21', '2021-03-12 21:39:21'),
(162, '<blockquote><p>If they instead find their origins in forms of experience, then the transitory importance of critical categories like \"alienation\" and \"everyday life,\" or the move to the forefront of the concept of \"reification\" during these years, must then be another sign of the upheaval in social relations occasioned by the sudden, full-scale entry of capital into \"style of life,\" into lived, daily, almost imperceptible rhythms.</p></blockquote>', 38, NULL, '5-6', NULL, '2021-03-12 22:21:24', '2021-03-12 22:21:24'),
(163, '<blockquote><p>The word <em>communication</em> was everywhere and yet the experience of communication itself, be it understood as spontaneous expression, reciprocity, or the contiguity necessary for reciprocity to exist, was precisely what was in the process of disappearing under the onslaught of merchandise and the new forms of media technologies.</p></blockquote>', 38, NULL, '6', NULL, '2021-03-12 22:30:24', '2021-03-12 22:30:24'),
(164, '<blockquote><p>I have tried instead throughout this book to hold the two stories [i.e. Americanization and decolonialization]in the tension of what I take to be their intricate relationship as it was lived then and as it continues into present.</p></blockquote>', 38, NULL, '7', NULL, '2021-03-12 22:44:56', '2021-03-12 22:44:56'),
(165, '<blockquote><p>With the waning of its empire, France turned to a form of interior colonialism; rational administrative techniques developed in the colonies were brought home and put to use side by side with new technological innovations such as advertising in reordering metropolitan, domestic society, the \"everyday life\" of its citizens.</p></blockquote>', 38, NULL, '7', NULL, '2021-03-12 23:08:19', '2021-03-12 23:08:27'),
(166, '<p>. Through exploring the entanglements of the collective and the personal, a physical walk serves as living inquiry that offers an opportunity to contemplate one’s relations with the land</p>', 40, NULL, '688', NULL, '2021-03-12 23:28:27', '2021-03-12 23:28:27'),
(167, '<p>At times the conversion from exterior to interior colonialism was facilitated by a literal transfer of personnel;</p>', 38, NULL, '8', NULL, '2021-03-12 23:33:18', '2021-03-12 23:33:18'),
(168, '<p>Having decisively slammed shut the door to the Algerian episode, colonialism itself was made to seem like a dusty archaism, as though it had not transpired in the twentieth century and in the personal histories of many people living today, as though it played only a tiny role in France\'s national history, and not role at all in its modern identity. One of the arguments of this book is that the very logic of (racial) exclusion that would \"keep the two stories separate\" is itself the outcome of the accelerated capitalist modernization the French state undertook in those years.</p>', 38, NULL, '9', NULL, '2021-03-13 00:03:08', '2021-03-13 00:03:08'),
(169, '<p>“Teaching and learning occur everywhere, not only in the classroom. Learning</p><p>occurs in the in-between spaces of liminality, between the lines of the poem … between</p><p>fiction and non-fiction” (p. 49).Pauline Sameshima (2008) </p>', 41, NULL, '51', NULL, '2021-03-13 16:36:59', '2021-03-13 16:36:59'),
(170, '<p> a/r/tography is at once a material and</p><p>conceptual practice always in a state of movement that exceeds any perceived products,</p><p>protocols, or practices, in order to embrace emergence, always in movement, always</p><p>becoming.</p>', 41, NULL, '51', NULL, '2021-03-13 16:40:38', '2021-03-13 16:40:38'),
(171, '<blockquote><p>The Baroque refers not to an essence but rather to an operative function, to a trait. It endlessly produces folds. It does not invent things: there are all kinds of folds coming from the East, Greek, Roma, Romanesque, Gothic, Classical folds. Yet the Baroque trait twists and turns its folds, pushing them to infinity, fold over fold, one upon the other. The Baroque fold unfurls all the way to infinity. First, the Baroque differentiates its folds in two ways by moving along two infinities, as if infinity were composed of two stages or floors: the pleats of matter, and the fold in the soul.</p></blockquote>', 43, NULL, '3', NULL, '2021-03-14 15:40:24', '2021-03-14 15:40:24'),
(172, '<blockquote><p>Though not himself an intellectual, the shah often impressed intellectuals. Gunnar Myrdal called him extraordinary after he and his wife visited with the shah and Queen Farah. Indeed, the two men were very impressed with each other. Their meeting, scheduled for a private luncheon, lasted several hours after the queen and Mrs. Myrdal left the table. The shah was familiar with Myrdal’s works on race problems in the United States and poverty in South Asia. Myrdal later commented that if there ever was a philosopher king, the shah was it. The shah admired people of Myrdal’s intellectual stature, more so if they were also statesmen — especially Léopold Sédar Senghor, the Senegalese poet and politician, one of the few friends with whom he was on first-name basis. He admired Senghor for his literary and philosophical bent and was taken with his discourse on “negritude” and especially his suggestion about “iranité” as an idea that could be developed as shorthand to identify Iran as a “cultural becoming” to bridge the East and the West. The shah might have wished he could put the thought poetically, but he could not. The best he could do was to use economic and technological language, which he did with comprehensiveness, sometimes with a smattering of exaggeration substituting for poetry. Perhaps this is why he felt more at ease with the technocrats,</p></blockquote>', 44, NULL, '56-7', NULL, '2021-03-14 17:37:44', '2021-03-14 17:37:44'),
(173, '<blockquote><p>The matter-fold is a matter-time; its characteristics resemble the continuous discharge of an \"infinity of wind muskets.\" And there still we can imagine the affinity of matter for life insofar as an \"infinity of wind-muskets.\"</p></blockquote>', 43, NULL, '7', NULL, '2021-03-14 21:57:47', '2021-03-14 21:57:47'),
(174, '<p>offering the young new ways of symbolizing,new ways of structuring their experince, so they can  see more, hear more, make more connections, embark on new and unfamiliar adventures into meaning.</p>', 45, NULL, '50', NULL, '2021-03-14 23:04:42', '2021-03-14 23:04:42'),
(175, '<blockquote><p>The organism is defined by its ability ti fold its own parts and to unfold them, not to infinity, but to a degree of development assigned to each species. Thus an organism is enveloped by organism, one within another (interlocking or germinal matter), like Russian dolls.</p></blockquote>', 43, NULL, '8', NULL, '2021-03-14 23:55:25', '2021-03-14 23:55:25'),
(176, '<p>Everything moves as if the pleats of matter possessed no reason in themselves. It is because the Fold is always between to folds, and because the between-two-folds seems to move about everywhere. </p>', 43, NULL, '13', NULL, '2021-03-15 02:06:08', '2021-03-15 02:06:08'),
(177, '<div class=\"rtl\"><blockquote><p>آثار هنرمندان خارجی در ایران بر پایه مبادلات فرهنگی (ماندد شرکت هنرمندان نوپرداز ایرانی در بی ینال ونیز و پاریس، و شرکت در جشنواره نقاشی مانی سورمر، لوهاور، گران پاله، سالن دوتن، سینه دزار، واش آرت، مرکز ایرانشناسی دانشگاه کلمبیا، ایشتار کالیفرنیا، مونترال کانادا، تورنتو، میلانوی ایتالیا، سویس، و متقابلا ارائه نمایشگاه بین المللی تهران با شرکت گالری های فرانسه ... ).</p><p>فعال شدن گالری های خصوصی ( مانند صبا، هنر جدید، تالار ایران/قندریز، بورگز، سیجون، مس، نگار، زروان، لیتو، مهر شاه، نقش، سامان، سولیوان، شهر، فصل هاویادها، کرته، زند، تهران گالری، لوترک، شیخ و نیازی) و نگارخانه های دولتی (مانند خانه آفتاب،تخت جمشید و کاخ جوانان). همچنین، توجه خاص انجمن های فرهنگی ایران و آمریکا و انتستیتو گوته و انجمن ایران و ایتالیا و انتستیتو ایان و فرانسه به هنر معاصر ایران ...</p><p>فعال شدن هنرمندان در جشن هنر شیراز و جشن فرهنگ و هنر و افزایش بورسیه و استفاده از سفرهای مطالعاتی دولتی و خصوصی و ایجاد مراکر هنری در ایران در خارج (خانه هنر پاریس و گالری سیروس)</p></blockquote></div>', 46, NULL, '158', NULL, '2021-03-15 18:00:54', '2021-03-15 18:02:55'),
(178, '<div class=\"rtl\"><blockquote><p>اگر چه حمایت دولتی از هنرمندان هنرهای تجسمی از اوایل دهه 30، از سوی اداره کل هنرهای زیبا  با شرکت دادن نوپردازان در چندنمایشگاه بزرگ رسمی، شروع شد، ما حمایت علنی و گسترده از جمع نوگرایان با بی ینال ها پاگرفت. ... از اولین بی ینال، اداره کل هنرهای زیبا (بعدا فرهنگ وهنر و فعلا ارشاد)، با توجه ویژه به نوگرایان و اختصاص سالن های کاخ ابیض  به نمایش کار آنان، مدرنیست ها را وارد مسابقه حذفی با هنرمندان سنتی کرد... بین سال های 1337 تا 1345 چالشی بین سنت گرایان با نوگرایان در گرفت. (159) ... هردو گروه مردم را داور این دعوا و آنان را منحصرا پشتیبان خود می دانستند.  ... نوپردازان پیروز شدندک چون نوگرایان خود را به مصلحت، هم سوی نوسازی کشور، نشان می دادند و می کوشیدند نوگرایی را در ادبیات و دیگر هنرها، خاصه نقاشی مدرن، فعالیتی منطبق با رشد مدنی و فرهنگی جاعه و تلاش در جهت تحول وضعیت، نشان دهند.</p></blockquote></div>', 46, NULL, '159-160', NULL, '2021-03-15 18:21:17', '2021-03-15 18:21:17'),
(179, '<div class=\"rtl\"><p>در نتیجه مقابله میان نوگراها و سنت گرا ها</p><blockquote><p>سوگلی های پیشین دربار و دستگاه رسمی هنری، واپس رانده شدند: مینیاتوریست ها به دکان های لاله زار و بازار، کلای های درس هنرستان یا به کنج کارگاه های آفرینش هنری وزارتخانه تبعید شدند.</p></blockquote></div>', 46, NULL, '160', NULL, '2021-03-15 20:13:45', '2021-03-15 20:13:45'),
(180, '<blockquote><p>Formerly Europeans with divine right, we were already feeling our dignity beginning to crumble under American or Soviet looks; Europe was already no more than a geographical accident, the peninsula that Asia shoves into the Atlantic. We were hoping at least to find a bit of our greatness reflected in the domesticated eyes of the Africans. But there are no more domesticated eyes: there are wild and free looks that judge our world.</p></blockquote>', 47, NULL, '14', NULL, '2021-03-16 17:33:44', '2021-03-16 17:33:44'),
(181, '<p>Being [l\'Etre] is black, Being is made of fire, we are accidental and far away, we have to justify our mores, our technics, our undercooked paleness and our verdigris vegetation.</p>', 47, NULL, '15', NULL, '2021-03-16 17:47:47', '2021-03-16 17:47:47'),
(182, '<blockquote><p>In a word, I am talking now to white men, and I should like to explain to them what black men already know: why it is necessarily through a poetic experience that the black man, in his present condition, must first become conscious of himself; and, inversely, why black poetry in the French language is, in our time, the only great revolutionary poetry.</p></blockquote>', 47, NULL, '16', NULL, '2021-03-16 17:57:31', '2021-03-16 17:57:31'),
(183, '<blockquote><p>It must therefore be recognized that it is the present circumstances of the class struggle that keep the worer from expressing himself poetically. Oppressed by technics, he wants to be a technician because he knows that technics will be instrument of his liberation; he knows that its is only by gainting professional, economic and scientific know-how that he will be able soneday to control business management. He now has a profound practical knosledge of what poets have called <em>Nature, but it is a knowledge he has gained more through his eyes: Nature is Matter for him--that crafty, inert adversity that he works on with his tools; Matter has no song.</em></p></blockquote>', 47, NULL, '16', NULL, '2021-03-16 18:19:21', '2021-03-16 18:19:21'),
(184, '<p>The white worker benefits somewhat from colonization, in spite of himself: low as his standard of living may be, it would be even lower if there were no colonization.</p>', 47, NULL, '19', NULL, '2021-03-16 18:33:23', '2021-03-16 18:33:23'),
(185, '<p>Thus the <em>black </em>is found to contain <em>all Evil </em>and <em>all Good, </em>it covers up an almost unbearable tension between two contradictory classifications: solar hierarchy and racial hierarchy. It gains thereby an extraordinary poetry, like self-destructive objects from the hand of Duchamp and the Surrealists; there is a secret blackness in white, a secret whiteness in black, fixed flickering of Being and of Non-being which is perhaps nowhere expressed as well as in this poem by Cesaire.</p>', 47, NULL, '28', NULL, '2021-03-16 20:56:55', '2021-03-16 20:56:55'),
(186, '<p>\"lived experience \" refering to past experiences that are assumed to be historically relocatable. the second is live experience, referring to \"ongoing experiences of the moment\"\"now as i pause to reflect\"Ted Aioki tell us,\" i myself lingering in the fold of doubled imaginaries-the ideographic and the calliographic.</p>', 48, NULL, '72', NULL, '2021-03-16 21:09:43', '2021-03-16 21:09:43'),
(187, '<p>Aoki enters \"a space textually accented with a mark: /, a graphically tectonic space, a space marked by differences neither strictly vertical nor strictly horizontal, a space that may allow generative possibilities.\" It is a space \"of generative interplay between planned curriculum and live(d) curriculum,\" space \"where newness can come into being.\" Connecting this new formulation with phenomenological language he has used in earlier essays he notes: \"It is an inspirited site of being and becoming.</p>', 48, NULL, '73', NULL, '2021-03-16 21:17:14', '2021-03-16 21:17:14'),
(188, '<p>spaces, he underlines, are \"edgy spaces, located at margins and boundaries, space of doubling, where \'this or that\' becomes \'this and that,\' ambiguously, ambivalent—difficult places but nonetheless spaces of generative possibilities.\" aioki</p>', 48, NULL, '73', NULL, '2021-03-16 21:19:34', '2021-03-16 21:19:34'),
(189, '<p>I call on fine arts educators in particular, with their strong sense of poetics, to offer inspiration and leadership in the promising work of creating a new landscape wherein \"live(d) curricula\" can become a legitimated signifier. We seek your guiding hand in re-shaping and re-constituting the landscape such that in generative third spaces earth\'s rhythms can be heard, at times in thunderous rolls and at other times in fingertip whispers, not only in fine arts classes but also throughout the school wherever teachers and students gather in the name of inspirited education.</p><p>Chapter</p>', 48, NULL, '74', NULL, '2021-03-16 21:22:04', '2021-03-16 21:22:04'),
(190, '<blockquote><p>Black is not color, it is the destruction of this borrowed clarity which falls from the white sun. The revolutionary negro is negation because he wishes to be complete nudity: in order to build his Truth, he must first destroy others\' Truth. Black faces--these night memories which haunt our days--embody the dark work of Negativity which patiently gnaws at concepts. Thus, by a reversal which curiously recalls that of the humiliated negro--insulted and called \"dirty nigger\" when he asserts his rights--it is the privative aspect of darkness that establishesh its value. Liberty is the color of night. Desctructions, <em>autodafes </em>of langiage, magic symbolism, ambivalence of concepts: all the negative aspects of modern poetry are here.</p></blockquote>', 47, NULL, '28', NULL, '2021-03-16 21:38:15', '2021-03-16 21:38:15'),
(191, '<blockquote><p>There are two convergence means of arriving at this primordial simplicity of existence: one is objective, the other subjective. The poets in our anthology sometimes use one, sometimes the other, and sometimes both of them together. In effect, there exists an objective negritude that is expressed by the more arts, chants and dances of the African populances. As a <em>spritual exerise,</em> the poet will prescribe allowing himself to be fascinated by primitive rhythms, letting his thoughts run in traditional forms of black poetry. ...The poet act, then, is a dance of the soul; the poet turns around and around like a dervish until he faints; he has established his ancestors\' time in himself, he feels it flowing with its peculiar violent pulls; he hopes to \"find\" himself in this shythmic pulsation.</p></blockquote>', 47, NULL, '29', NULL, '2021-03-16 22:19:49', '2021-03-16 22:19:49'),
(192, '<blockquote><p>One must dive under the superficial crust of reality, of common sense, of reasoning reason, in order to touch the very bottom of the soul and awaken the timeless forces of desire: desire which makes of man a refusal of everything and a love of everything; desire, the radical negation of natural laws and of the possible, a call to miracles; desire which, by its mad cosmic energy, plunges man back into the seething breast of Nature and, at the same time, lifts him above Nature through the affirmation of his Right to be unsatisfied.</p></blockquote>', 47, NULL, '31', NULL, '2021-03-16 22:57:14', '2021-03-16 22:57:14'),
(193, '<blockquote><p>Many have believed that surrealism was dead. Many wrote so. Childish nonsense: its activity extends today to the entire world and surrealism remains livelier, more audacious than ever. ...Actually, today as twenty years ago, surrealism can claim the glory of being at the extreme point of the bow of life drawn to the breaking point.</p></blockquote>', 50, NULL, '34', NULL, '2021-03-20 14:06:19', '2021-03-20 14:06:19'),
(194, '<blockquote><p>When Breton created surrealism, the most urgent task was to free the mind from the shackles of absurd logic and the so-called Western reason.</p></blockquote>', 50, NULL, '35', NULL, '2021-03-20 14:08:59', '2021-03-20 14:08:59'),
(195, '<blockquote><p>So, far from contradicting, diminishing, or diverting our revolutionary feeling for life, surrealism shored it up. It nourished in us an impatient strength, endlessly sustaining this massive army of negations. </p><p>And then I think also to tomorrow. (37)</p><p>Millions of Black hands, across the region clouds of world war, will spread terror everywhere. Roused from a long benumbing torpor, this most deprived of all people will rise up, upon plains of ashes. </p><p>Our surrealism will then supply them the leaven from their very depths. It will be time finally to transcend the sordid contemporary antinomies: White-Blacks, Europeans-Africans, civilized-savage: the powerful magic of the mahoulis will be recovered, drawn from the very wellsprings of life. Colonia idiocies will be purified by the wekdiing arc\'s blue flame. The mettle of our metal, our cutting edge of steel, our unique communions--all will be recovered.</p><p>Surrealism, tightrope of our hope.</p></blockquote>', 50, NULL, '37-38', NULL, '2021-03-20 14:27:14', '2021-03-20 14:27:14'),
(196, '<p>It is in this in-between space that chaos is appreciated alongside order, complexity alongside simplicity, and uncertainty alongside certainty. These complex spaces are attuned to invention and the possibility of poetic wisdom. Our minds and bodies are inseparable, making perceptual awareness simultaneously felt, imagined and abstract. We actively create knowledge through sensing, feeling and thinking. Through aesthetics of attunement, unfolding, and/or surrender, we linger in dynamic in-between spaces.</p>', 51, NULL, '62', NULL, '2021-03-20 23:25:14', '2021-03-20 23:25:14'),
(197, '<p>Information flows freely while recognizing restraint, and diversity is celebrated while recognizing conformity. Tensions between these polarities are held within a dialectical balance, a balance that invigorates novelty, surprise, and humour. Tensions entice shifting arrangements ensuring fluid, yet dynamic stability and instability. Temporal rhythms provide enough regularity for coordinated actions while allowing for change, shifting patterns, and spontaneous responses.</p><p>Spatial connections ensure comfort while offering opportunities for innovation.</p><p></p>', 51, NULL, '64', NULL, '2021-03-20 23:28:43', '2021-03-20 23:28:43'),
(198, '<p>Unfolding, opening, evolving, expanding, manifesting, laying open one’s sensory awareness, understandings of beauty, and perceptual sensibility. An aesthetic awareness is open to wonder ness is open to wonder while suspending belief and trusting uncertainty ness is open to wonder while suspending belief and trusting uncertainty</p>', 51, NULL, '64', NULL, '2021-03-20 23:32:53', '2021-03-20 23:32:53'),
(199, '<blockquote><div class=\"rtl\"><p>\"یک قفل کوچک که در ایران به وسیله دست ساخته شده است، برای من خیلی خیال انگیز تر از پر هیاهوترین پدیده های غرب است. من فکر می کنم این شعر ماست که اصولا مارا به هنرهای دیگر نزدیک می کند؛ و بی جهت نیست که من دوست دارم نمایشگاه هایم توام با شعر باشد، مثل نمایشگاه قبلی گروه پنج که در انستیتوی گوته تشکیل شد و شاعران زیادی در شب های شعر--در همان زمان--شرکت کردند...\" </p></div></blockquote><div class=\"rtl\"><p>تناولی (رودکی آبان 1351)</p></div>', 46, NULL, '193', NULL, '2021-03-21 19:34:02', '2021-03-21 19:34:02'),
(200, '<blockquote><p>1925: In the wake of the First Surrealist Manifesto, the movement begins to make itself notorious. France is engaged in a minor war with anticolonial rebeles in Morocco; Breton and Company sympathize with the insurgents. At a banquet in honor of the symbolist poet Saint-Pol-Roux, a mellee erupts between the surrealists and conservative patriots. Epithets fly:  <em>Vive l\'Allemagne!</em> rings out; Philippe Soupault swings from a chandelier, kicking over bottles and glasses. Michel Leiris is soon at an open window, denouncing France to the growing crowd. A riot ensues; Leiris, nearly lynched, is arrested and manhandled by the police.</p></blockquote>', 53, NULL, '543', NULL, '2021-03-23 03:15:11', '2021-03-23 03:15:11'),
(201, '<blockquote><p>It will sometimes be difficult to distinguish technique from: (1) the arts and fine arts, since aesthetic activity and technical activity are on par as regard creativity. In the plastic arts, no differentiation can be established other than the one that exists in the belief system if the artists; (2) religious efficacy. The difference lies entirely in how the native conceives of the efficacy. It is therefore to estimate the respective proportions of technique and magical efficacy in the native\'s mind (e.g. poisoned arrows).</p></blockquote>', 54, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2021-03-23 17:46:31', '2021-03-23 17:46:31'),
(202, '<p>Mauss\'s technological engagements were of an altogether different sort as we can imagine, ...</p>', 54, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2021-03-23 19:00:34', '2021-03-23 19:01:56'),
(203, '<blockquote><p>Techniques are to be defined as <em>traditional actions combined in order to produce a mechanical, physical, or chemical effect, these actions being recognized to have that effect.</em></p><ol><li><p>the arts and fine arts, since aesthetic activity and technical activity are on a par as regards creativity. In the plastic arts, no differentiation can be established other than the one that exists in the belief system of artist;</p><ol><li><p>religious efficacy. The difference lies entirely in how the native coceives of the efficacy. It is therefore necessary to estimate the respective proportions of technique and magical efficay in the native\'s mind.</p></li></ol></li></ol></blockquote>', 54, NULL, '98', NULL, '2021-03-24 04:13:15', '2021-03-24 04:13:15'),
(204, '<blockquote><p>The mistake of Karl Marx is that he believed the economy to condition techniques: the converse is true.</p></blockquote>', 54, NULL, '98', NULL, '2021-03-24 04:15:36', '2021-03-24 04:15:36'),
(205, '<blockquote><p>The sum of bodily habits [<em>habitus du corps</em>] is a technique that is taught, and whose evolution has not yet come to an end. The technique of swimming improves day by day.</p><p>Body techniques should be studied with the aid of photography and if possible with slow-motion cinema</p></blockquote>', 54, NULL, '99', NULL, '2021-03-24 17:27:07', '2021-03-24 17:27:07'),
(206, '<p>As a ‘lifeworld’ (Seamon, 1980, p. 149) practice, walking is an unconscious</p><p>way of moving through urban space, enabling us to sense our bodies and the features of the environment. With one foot-after-the other, we flow continuously and rhythmically while traversing urban place. Walking is an experience we are not conscious of, ignoring its potential as an aesthetic, creative or simply insightful practice. It is while walking that we sensorially and reflectively interact with the urban environment, firming up our relationship with urban places. Walking practices and ‘senses of (or for) place’ are fundamentally related, the former affecting the latter and vice versa. Furthermore, walking and ‘walkscapes’ are rhythmical. While ‘walking’ in the city, we perform in space-time, becoming immersed in temporal continuums of social everyday life activities fused with spatial and natural rhythmical events.</p>', 55, NULL, '125', NULL, '2021-03-24 21:19:30', '2021-03-24 21:19:30'),
(207, '<p>Consciousness is being toward the thing through the intermediary of the body. A movement is learned when the body has understood it, that is, when it has incorporated it into its ‘world’, and to move one’s body is to aim at things through it; it is to allow oneself to respond to their call, which is made upon it independently of any representation. Motility, then, is not, as it were, a handmaid of consciousness, transporting the body to that point in space of which we have formed a representation beforehand. In order that we may be able to move our body towards an object, the object must first exist for it, our body must not belong to the realm of the ‘in-itself — Merleau-Ponty (1962, pp.138-9).</p><p>Me</p><p></p>', 56, NULL, '46', NULL, '2021-03-24 21:31:56', '2021-03-24 21:31:56');
INSERT INTO `codes` (`id`, `body`, `reference_id`, `notes`, `pages`, `deleted_at`, `created_at`, `updated_at`) VALUES
(208, '<p>A movement is learned when the body has understood it, that is, when it has incorporated it into its ‘world’, and to move one’s body is to aim at things through it; it is to allow oneself to respond to their call, which is made upon it independently of any representation.Merleau-Ponty (1962, pp.138-9)</p>', 56, NULL, '46', NULL, '2021-03-25 00:38:06', '2021-03-25 00:38:36'),
(209, '<p>‘my body has its world, or understands its world, without having to make use of my “symbolic” or “objectifying” function’ (1962, pp.140-1). Movements</p>', 56, NULL, 'i', NULL, '2021-03-25 00:47:01', '2021-03-25 00:47:01'),
(210, '<p>Movements of the body are not directed by this conscious force — the ‘“symbolic” and “objectifying” function’ — but by the body’s intelligent connections with the world at hand:</p><p>My flat is, for me, not a set of closely associated images. It remains a familiar domain round about me only as long as I have ‘in my arms’ or ‘in my legs’ the main distances involved, and as long as from my body intentional threads run out towards it (1962, p. 130).</p>', 56, NULL, '46', NULL, '2021-03-25 18:02:54', '2021-03-25 18:02:54'),
(211, '<p>Movements are learned when the body has understood them, and this understanding can be described as a set of invisible but intelligent ‘threads’ which run out between body and the world with which the body is familiar. This picture of movement corresponds to group descriptions above — the arms turning the wheel, the legs taking the person to the required destination, the feet carefully choosing a resting place in the stream-bed. The body has within itself the power to initiate these directed movements before and without a need for cognition to screen the world at hand and then implement orders.</p>', 56, NULL, '64', NULL, '2021-03-25 18:06:29', '2021-03-25 18:06:29'),
(212, '<p>Reactions are not, therefore, a succession of events; they have in themselves an ‘intelligibility’ (Merleau-Ponty, 1963, cited in Zaner, 1971, p. 154).</p><p>Merleau-Ponty</p>', 56, NULL, '64', NULL, '2021-03-25 18:10:23', '2021-03-25 18:10:23'),
(213, '<p>Body-subject learns through action. Movements become familiar when the body performs them several times and incorporates them into its world of prereflective understanding. </p>', 56, NULL, '48', NULL, '2021-03-25 18:15:16', '2021-03-25 18:15:16'),
(214, '<p>Bodily involvement must be active. The movement will not be</p><p>learned if the body is passive and the movement conducted separately from the body’s direct participation. One group member, for example, explained that the past summer she had ridden the same bus route from her home to work each day (1.8.2). When a friend volunteered to drive her one morning, however, she could not give him directions. Body- subject was passively carried to a destination. It had not actively performed</p>', 56, NULL, '48', NULL, '2021-03-25 18:41:42', '2021-03-25 18:41:42'),
(215, '<p>Body-subject learns through repetition and therefore requires time</p><p>to familiarise itself with the world in which it finds itself. Once</p>', 56, NULL, '48', NULL, '2021-03-25 18:45:28', '2021-03-25 18:45:28'),
(216, '<p>Body- subject is conservative in nature and prefers that movements adhere to their patterns of the past. This fact has important implications for environmental policy and design. </p>', 56, NULL, '49', NULL, '2021-03-25 18:49:32', '2021-03-25 18:49:32'),
(217, '<p>Repetition is crucial to the behaviourist definition of learning, which is defined as the ability to repeat certain gestures fixed as habits after a period of trial and error (Hilgard et al., 1974, p.189).</p>', 56, NULL, '49', NULL, '2021-03-25 19:56:19', '2021-03-25 19:56:19'),
(218, '<p>Phenomenologists recognise the importance of repetition in bodily</p><p>learning, but interpret it as an active endeavour of body by which its powers as subject are extended. </p>', 56, NULL, '50', NULL, '2021-03-25 20:00:23', '2021-03-25 20:00:23'),
(219, '<p>Bodily learning is not a sequence of responses established through reinforcement. It is the body’s grasping understanding fostered through action.</p>', 56, NULL, '64', NULL, '2021-03-25 20:01:39', '2021-03-25 20:01:39'),
(220, '<p>Learning is not the fixation of a particular gesture as a response to a particular situation but rather the establishment of general attitude with regard to the structure or essence of the situation’ (Bannan, 1967, p.38). </p>', 56, NULL, '50', NULL, '2021-03-25 20:12:59', '2021-03-25 20:12:59'),
(221, '<p>Body-subject establishes a general attitude towards particular tasks and to some degree can creatively vary its behaviours.</p><p></p>', 56, NULL, '51', NULL, '2021-03-25 20:17:03', '2021-03-25 20:17:03'),
(222, '<blockquote><p>The combination of techniques constitutes industries and crafts. Techniques, industries and crafts, taken together, constitute the technical system of a society, which is essential to it. A correct observation of this system will have to respect the different proportions of its constituents.</p></blockquote>', 54, NULL, '98', NULL, '2021-03-25 23:53:40', '2021-03-25 23:53:40'),
(223, '<p>Movement and rest are not isolated phenomena: they exist together in dialectic.2 There is a continuous tension between the two which leads to a series of resolutions. ‘Man’, says the architect Aldo van Eyck (cited in Norberg-Schulz, 1971, p.33), ‘is both center bound and horizon bound.’ Movement leads to rest which in turn leads to movement. This</p>', 56, NULL, '132', NULL, '2021-03-27 19:56:08', '2021-03-27 19:56:08'),
(224, '<p>It points to</p><p>a basic human need for spatial and environmental familiarity and order. Rest anchors the person’s present in his or her past; it maintains experiential continuity. Security, privacy, quiet, passivity, contemplation and other similar qualities often have their context in rest.</p>', 56, NULL, '134', NULL, '2021-03-27 19:58:19', '2021-03-27 19:58:19'),
(225, '<p>The deepest experience of rest is dwelling, which brings people</p><p>together and people and nature together in terms of place. The world of dwelling involves regularity, repetition and cyclicity all grounded in care and concern; it is, as Jager says, a ‘round world’:</p><p>The round world of dwelling offers a cyclical time, that is, the recurring times of seasons, of the cycles of birth and death, of planting and harvesting, of meeting and meeting again, of doing and doing over again. It offers a succession of crops, of duties, generations, forever appearing and reappearing. It offers a place where fragile objects and creatures can be tended and cared for through constant, gentle reoccurring contacts (1975, p.251)</p>', 56, NULL, '133', NULL, '2021-03-27 20:08:38', '2021-03-27 20:08:38'),
(226, '<p>A person, through movement, extends his knowledge of distance, place and experience; he becomes familiar with spatial and experiential horizons that were undisclosed or obscure before. </p>', 56, NULL, '133', NULL, '2021-03-27 20:14:17', '2021-03-27 20:14:17'),
(227, '<p>Movement helps the person to assimilate places and situations into his world of familiarity. In this sense, movement widens the sphere of at-homeness and dwelling. Jager</p>', 56, NULL, '133', NULL, '2021-03-27 20:15:35', '2021-03-27 20:15:35'),
(228, '<p>Movement, in contrast, has links with horizon, reach and unfamiliarity. It is associated with such active qualities as search, newness, exploration, alertness and exertion.</p>', 56, NULL, '133', NULL, '2021-03-27 20:16:14', '2021-03-27 20:16:14'),
(229, '<p>Jager (ibid.) discusses movement in terms of journey, which he finds</p><p>a common theme not only in travelling, exploring and sight-seeing, but also in intellectual, artistic and spiritual efforts. The journey carries the person away from his stable world of dwelling. It gives him a sense of forward and back, past and future; and moves him outward along a path towards confrontation — with places, experiences, ideas:</p>', 56, NULL, '133', NULL, '2021-03-27 20:18:46', '2021-03-27 20:18:46'),
(230, '<p>Journeying breaks open the circle of the sun and the seasons and forms it into a linear pattern of succession in which the temporal world shrinks to a before and after, to backward and forward. Here the beginning is no longer felt to lie in the middle but instead appears placed behind one’s back. The future makes its appearance straight ahead, making possible confrontation (ibid.,</p>', 56, NULL, '133', NULL, '2021-03-28 02:15:04', '2021-03-28 02:15:04'),
(231, '<p>Movement and rest, because of their dialectical nature, each incorporate</p><p>aspects of the other. They are not mutually exclusive but often</p><p>encompass qualities more often associated with the opposite.</p><p>The afternoon constitutional, for example, first suggests movement. As an experience, however, this daily walk through a regular sequence of paths and places typically involves no adventure or unfamiliarity. It may, however, invigorate the walker and renew his depleted energies. Here, an action which in appearance suggests movement provides an inner function associated with rest. Rest and movement exist together, and each shares aspects of the other</p>', 56, NULL, '134', NULL, '2021-03-28 02:45:06', '2021-03-28 02:45:06'),
(232, '<p>walking in nature become ways to evoke spiritual and aesthetic responses that provoke a deeper understanding of self-cre ation through an active pedagogy of self. Three themes are explored through a walking curre</p>', 57, NULL, '1', NULL, '2021-03-30 16:25:11', '2021-03-30 16:25:11'),
(233, '<p>“curriculum,” touching down almost randomly through the centu-ries to see what changes there have been in its meaning.It is, of course, a Latin word carried directly over into English. Its first</p><p>Latin meaning was “a running,” “a race,” “a course,” with secondary mean-ings of a “race-course,” “a career.”</p>', 58, NULL, '10', NULL, '2021-04-03 22:54:28', '2021-04-03 22:55:05'),
(234, '<blockquote><p>By tracing the origion of the Weimar cyborg in Berlin Dada art, this book expands the concepts beyond its initial definition as an organic-technological hybrid to encompass a series of interrelated meanings, including, the cyborg as representing hybrid entity in a broader sense and as the locus of new modes of (interior and exterior) awareness created by the impact of technology on human perception.</p></blockquote>', 59, NULL, '1', NULL, '2021-04-04 21:00:06', '2021-04-04 21:00:06'),
(235, '<p>The term <em>cyborg </em>never appeared in Weimar culture and was invented much later. Yet the term is useful, it suggests how the interwar artistic and visual cultures in Germany anticipated much of the cultural discourse around the cyborg and cybernetics in the United States and Europe since the 1940s, both theoretical and practical as well as popular.</p>', 59, NULL, '2', NULL, '2021-04-04 21:03:21', '2021-04-04 21:03:21'),
(236, '<blockquote><p>Information, the same medium that made human beings like computers and machines, also made them more like one another. To view human beings as cybernetic systems was thus to recognize their collaborative natures: they were individuals created through information exchange and implementation.</p></blockquote>', 59, NULL, '4', NULL, '2021-04-04 21:26:02', '2021-04-04 21:26:02'),
(237, '<blockquote><p>For Haraway, the cyborg defined a fundamentally hybrid form of human identity that understood traditional distinctions between gender, race, and class. Furthermore, the cyborg also broke down three crucial distinctions that had previously defined the difference between human and nonhumans.</p></blockquote>', 59, NULL, '5', NULL, '2021-04-04 21:36:00', '2021-04-04 21:36:00'),
(238, '<p>Like Wiener, Haraway thus emphasized that the cyborg was a creature that fundamentally functioned through receiving, transmitting, and controlling information, a \"substance\" that, because of the multiple media into which it could be translated, often appeared to be insubstantial or noncorporeal. And these noncorporeal aspects of the cyborg often made it seem uncanny, magical, mystical, or even monstrous.</p>', 59, NULL, '6', NULL, '2021-04-04 21:42:55', '2021-04-04 21:42:55'),
(239, '<blockquote><p>It is only more recently that the subjects that Berlin Dadaists treated--and the social, political, and psychological issues that were represented--have come under scrutiny.</p></blockquote>', 59, NULL, '10', NULL, '2021-04-05 00:12:00', '2021-04-05 00:12:00'),
(240, '<p>by ..., I wish to identify a characteristic of the historical avant-garde that has yet to be given the attention it deserves...</p>', 59, NULL, '10', NULL, '2021-04-05 00:15:00', '2021-04-05 00:15:00'),
(241, '<blockquote><p>Although the Berlin Dadaists claimed to reject the German expressionists\' art and philosophies in their entirety, in actual practice the Dadaists rejected only certain aspects of expressionism while continuing others. ... The Dadaists heaped scorn on the expressionists\' desire to achieve forms of subjective or \'spiritual expression through their art, and the Dadaist recourse to nontraditional forms of art-making... can be seen as rejecting expressionists\' emphasis on traditional artistic materials (e.g. painting, sculpture, and printmaking) and their valorization of the artist\'s \"hand\" or gesture as a key way to express their subjective attitudes toward what they depicted. In addition, the Dadaists\' focus on mechanical imagery can also be seen as reaction to the expressionists\' stress on organic forms. At the same time, the Dadaists seemed to continuie aspects of the exprssionists\' primitivism in that certain types of Dada production suggest a belief that non-Western forms could help them achieve more direct relationship to the shapes and practices of modern life.</p></blockquote>', 59, NULL, '12', NULL, '2021-04-05 00:49:01', '2021-04-05 00:49:01'),
(242, '<blockquote><p>As Nikos Papastergiadis argued, hybridity is intimately related to primitivism. Because of its roots in nineteenth-century scientific and colonialist discourse, hybridity was initially defined in terms of a mixing between Europeans and non-European \"others,\" an understanding later absorbed into the concept of primitivism in art. Because of their conflicted relationship to artistic primitivism, it is thus not surprising that the Dadaists would have wrestled with ideas of hybridity and, moreover, they have reevaluated hybridity as something positive to how it was originally assessed--namely, as weak, debased, or sick--in the discourse of nineteenth-century \"scientific\" racism.</p></blockquote>', 59, NULL, '12', NULL, '2021-04-05 01:02:41', '2021-04-05 01:02:41'),
(243, '<blockquote><p>Thus, when the Berlin Dadaist presented the cyborg as representing a new form of hybrid modern \"identity,\" they influenced by a wide variety of conceptual systems already in place in their culture that modeled subjectivity as cyborgian, that is, as systematic, constructed, and mutable.</p></blockquote>', 59, NULL, '13', NULL, '2021-04-05 01:07:11', '2021-04-05 01:07:11'),
(244, '<blockquote><p>Dadaist representations of cyborgs, in other words, were presented as potential ego ideals--images of alternative forms of existence that could provoke their audience to rethink who and what they were. ... The Dada syborg helped the Dadaists and ehir audiences reflect on the changes in how they thought, acted, perceived and existed as a result of technology\'s impact on their bodies and minds, and it allowed them to imagine how to cope with and integrate thse alternations so as to better exist ion the moden world.</p></blockquote>', 59, NULL, '14', NULL, '2021-04-05 01:25:10', '2021-04-05 01:27:54'),
(245, '<blockquote><p>In art history and art criticism today, \"modernism\" is generally taken to indicate transformation in nineteenth- and early-twentieth0century Western painting and sculpture whereby various artists systematically negated their representational traditions and developed new forms of abstract signification. These changes led in at lest two different directions. First, modernism influenced certain artists to examine and criticize the various myths of self and world to which bourgeois society subscribed. Second, it inspired others to examine perception and later the media of painting and sculpture.</p></blockquote>', 59, NULL, '19', NULL, '2021-04-05 01:51:37', '2021-04-05 01:51:37'),
(246, '<p>...postmodernism seemed to reject the modernist focus on interrogating the properties of specific media treated in isolation from one another. Instead, it embraced heterogeneity in art (i.e. the mixing of multiple media in a single work) and affirmed the idea of visual art\'s interconnectedness with other forms of modernist (and premodernist) art and mass culture, such as literature, music, poetry, theater, photography, and film.</p>', 59, NULL, '19', NULL, '2021-04-05 01:56:10', '2021-04-05 01:56:10'),
(247, '<blockquote><p>...the historical avant-garde also fundamentally transformed its forms, materials, and practices. Firsts, by radically widening the criteria as to what could count as art, the historical avant-garde broke down all notions of teleology in relation tot he historical  development of Western art. ...Second, the avant-garde produced a new type of artist unrestricted to a particular style, technique, or medium, who used the various forms and strategies of the mass media to produce artworks. ...Third, avant-gare works tended more and more to emphesize montage. Often possessing only a partial or an incomplete unity, they required, in extreme cases, an engaged spectator or reader to bring coherence to the work\'s heterogeneous elemets. And it was mainly by breaking through the appearances of totality and negating unified form or subject matter that avant-garde works got their bried and relatively ineffectual social-critical power: their ability to expose art\'s instituitional structures and the spectator\'s role in constructing aesthetic and, by implication, social experience. Fourthm avant-garde works were much more open to the external world than bouegeois modern art. ... In adition, avant-garde artists also emplotyed strategies of chane and automatism to allow something external to imprint itself on the work: a trace of an other variousky understood to be objective, natural, unconscious, or even divine. Fifth, avant-garde artists focused on the singular, thereby producing melancholy representation that implied both historical loss and the beielf that reality could never be fully conceptualized or shaped.</p></blockquote>', 59, NULL, '20', NULL, '2021-04-05 02:34:45', '2021-04-05 02:34:45'),
(248, '<blockquote><p>Burger\'s theory of the avant-garde has been rightly criticized for devaluing \"neo-avant-garde\" art after World War II and overvaluing the \"original\" avant-garde break from aestheticism.</p></blockquote>', 59, NULL, '21', NULL, '2021-04-05 02:50:21', '2021-04-05 02:50:21'),
(249, '<p>For this reason, it is better to understand avant-garde art as a mode of modernism, albeit one that transformed modern art in different ways. In addition to radically expanding the materials and media in and through which art could be made, the historical avant-garde also explicitly recognized fine art\'s fundamental interconnectections with mass culture--something that modern art alluded to and used, but which it also attempted to disavow. ...In addition, the historical avant-garde also represented a turn to identity  politics in art: there representation of alternative forms of subjectivity such as those evoked by the figure of the cyborg.</p>', 59, NULL, '21', NULL, '2021-04-05 02:59:43', '2021-04-05 02:59:43'),
(250, '<blockquote><p>Avant-garde art, in turn, was a response to the perceived bankruptcy of modern art--a response to the realization that modernism  only pretended to reject bourgeois culture and that it really perpetuated its ideals in the form of partial negations. As a result, avant-garde art rejected modernist formalism--albeit not comepletely--and, in adddition to continuing central aspects of modernism\'s first trajectory, it added something new: the project of imagining nonbourgeois forms of subjectivity more adequate to the modern world.</p></blockquote>', 59, NULL, '21-22', NULL, '2021-04-05 03:12:57', '2021-04-05 03:12:57'),
(251, '<p>A/r/tography is a practice of living enquiry that combines life-writing with life-creating. </p>', 60, NULL, '355', NULL, '2021-04-07 22:50:55', '2021-04-07 22:50:55'),
(252, '<p>A/r/tography is a practice of living enquiry that combines life-writing with life-creating. It promotes artistic enquiry as an aesthetic awareness, one that is open to wonder while trusting uncertainty. Through attention to memory, identity, autobiography, reflection, meditation, storytelling and cultural production, artists/researchers/teachers/learners expose their living practices in both evocative and provocative ways (Irwin 2013).</p>', 60, NULL, '355', NULL, '2021-04-07 22:52:45', '2021-04-07 22:52:45'),
(253, '<p>Rita Irwin describes</p><p>how her attention has shifted from what an art education practice might mean to exploring what art education, as a ‘practice set in motion’ (2013: 198),</p>', 60, NULL, '356', NULL, '2021-04-07 23:24:46', '2021-04-07 23:24:46'),
(254, '<p>becoming is an emergent immersive process that exists in the liminal multiple lines of flight and multiple encounters that encourage experimentation and improvisation.</p>', 60, NULL, '355', NULL, '2021-04-07 23:32:15', '2021-04-07 23:32:15'),
(255, '<p>A/r/tography as Practice-based Research, “a/r/tography radically transforms the idea of theory as an abstract system distinct and separate from practice. In its place, theory is understood as a critical exchange that is reflective, responsive and relational, which is continuously in a state of reconstruction and becoming something else altogether” (p.xiv).</p><p></p>', 61, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2021-04-09 00:42:05', '2021-04-09 00:42:05'),
(256, '<p>Writing about personal experiences is not only egoism, solipsism, unseemly</p><p>confession, boring prattling, and salacious revelation. We need to write personally because we live personally, and our personal living is always braided with our other ways of living—professional, academic, administrative, artistic, social, and political. </p>', 61, NULL, '5', NULL, '2021-04-09 00:44:58', '2021-04-09 00:44:58'),
(257, '<p>Walking methodologies privilege an embodied way of knowing where move- ment connects mind, body, and environment. Walking scholars typically describe embodiment as relational, social, and convivial. Embodiment is conventionally understood through phenomenology, where researchers and participants examine he lived experiences of what it means to move in a particular place. This expe- riential understanding either focuses on an individual account of a walker, or is conceptualized through community-based or group walking practices that high- light the social aspects of walking.</p><p></p>', 62, NULL, '4', NULL, '2021-04-10 23:47:38', '2021-04-10 23:47:38'),
(258, '<p>Rhythm is described through embodied accounts of moving and sensory expressions of feet, limbs, and breath. In other instances, rhythm pertains to the pulse of the city, such as traffi c, crowds, music, and other environmental phenomena that press on a walker.</p>', 62, NULL, '5', NULL, '2021-04-10 23:53:12', '2021-04-10 23:53:12'),
(259, '<p>Phil Jones and James Evans (2012 ) write that “humans layer their own under- standings onto abstract space in order to create subjective places” (p. 2319).</p>', 62, NULL, '18', NULL, '2021-04-11 00:10:22', '2021-04-11 00:10:22'),
(260, '<p>Tim Cresswell (2004 ) counters this understanding, suggesting that “most places are the products of everyday practices. Places are never fi nished but pro- duced through the reiteration of practices – the repetition of seemingly mundane practices on a daily basis” (p. 82).</p>', 62, NULL, '18', NULL, '2021-04-11 00:11:18', '2021-04-11 00:11:18'),
(261, '<p>Place, as such, is conceived of as a process. The idea of place and space as separate distinctions for Tim Ingold (2000 ) is fraught with problems. People, he argues, do not live in a place, but move through, around, and between them, such that places are more akin to knots “and the threads from which they are tied are lines of wayfaring” (p. 33). Wayfaring is less a path from point A to B, and more of a meshwork of lines and movement, “a trail along which life is lived” ( Ingold, 2011 , p. 69)</p>', 62, NULL, '18', NULL, '2021-04-11 00:12:36', '2021-04-11 00:12:36'),
(262, '<p>Space, writes Massey (2005), is contingent and in fl ux, “the product of interrelations,” and is “always under construction” (p. 9). If space is open and place cannot be assigned a prior location, then we need differ- ent ways to articulate place-making</p>', 62, NULL, '19', NULL, '2021-04-11 00:14:14', '2021-04-11 00:14:14'),
(263, '<p>Furthermore, environmentalism and even eco-feminism imply that the only way to know or understand nature is through immersion, which entails walking. This, she writes, ignores “the complicated histories of who is granted permission to enter nature, where nature is said to reside, how one must move in order to get there, and how one will interact with nature once one arrives in it” (p. 132)</p>', 62, NULL, '23', NULL, '2021-04-11 00:18:28', '2021-04-11 00:18:28'),
(264, '<p>The Latin infinitive of curriculum— currere— I invoked in 1975 to empha- size the lived experience of curriculum, embodied potentially educational experience that is structured by the past while focused on the future. </p>', 63, NULL, '50', NULL, '2021-05-05 13:17:49', '2021-05-05 13:17:49'),
(265, '<p>The running of the course— currere— occurs through conversation, ongoing dialogical encounter among students and teachers in classrooms but also within oneself in solitude. </p>', 63, NULL, '52', NULL, '2021-05-05 13:25:54', '2021-05-05 13:25:54'),
(266, '<p>the concept of currere redefines the meaning of the curriculum as complicated conversation. Indeed, currere emphasizes the everyday experience of the individual and one’s capacity to learn from that experience (e.g., to reconstruct experience through thought and self- reflection in the service of understanding).</p>', 63, NULL, '52', NULL, '2021-05-05 13:26:54', '2021-05-05 13:26:54'),
(267, '<p>No longer a noun only, curriculum is now a verb as well: currere, the Latin infinitive form of curriculum, means to run the course, emphasizing one’s lived experience of curriculum.</p>', 63, NULL, '52', NULL, '2021-05-05 14:00:50', '2021-05-05 14:00:50'),
(268, '<p>and dialogical encounter, currere has a method, with four steps or phases. In sum, the method of currere redefines curriculum: no longer course objectives or test outcomes, but complicated conversation among those studying the world through academic knowledge</p>', 63, NULL, '52', NULL, '2021-05-05 14:02:28', '2021-05-05 14:02:28'),
(269, '<p>Such language and imagery has cast the collapse of empires and the rise of new nation-states in the decades after World War II as a consensual process, a peaceful transfer of sovereignty.</p>', 64, NULL, '2', NULL, '2021-05-09 22:19:30', '2021-05-09 22:19:30'),
(270, '<p>Nothing could have been farther from the truth: decolonialization was a violent, fiercely contested process that pitted imperial rulers against colonial subjects.</p>', 64, NULL, '2', NULL, '2021-05-09 22:20:11', '2021-05-09 22:21:04'),
(271, '<p>Sense</p><p>of place refers to attachment to a place, whether one is a visitor or a resident (Jordan-Bychkov et al., 2006).</p>', 66, NULL, '5', NULL, '2021-05-17 16:13:59', '2021-05-17 16:13:59'),
(272, '<p>Tuan also highlights the distinction between the resident and the visitor’s view of a place. Placelessness describes those places that look the same no matter where one goes—in particular the commercial strip with fast food establishments and other franchises—which reflect the influences of popular culture (Jordan-Bychkov et al., 2006). Norton (2006), however, argues that people who live or work in these places do become attached to them</p>', 66, NULL, '5', NULL, '2021-05-17 16:15:08', '2021-05-17 16:15:08'),
(273, '<p>Margaret Rodman (1992, p. 641) writes, “… places are not inert containers. They are politicized, culturally relative, historically specific, local and multiple constructions.” In other words, places are symbolic articulations of personal, political, historical, economic, and social relationships (Casey, 1996).</p>', 66, NULL, '9', NULL, '2021-05-17 16:35:12', '2021-05-17 16:35:12'),
(274, '<blockquote><p>Avant-garde challenges to academicism and aestheticism are due in part to the failure of the liberal ideology under which the latter were spawned. Herein lies the tension between their internationalism and nationalist jingoism.</p></blockquote>', 68, NULL, '56', NULL, '2021-05-19 14:24:20', '2021-05-19 14:24:20'),
(275, '<blockquote><p>It may be that universal history is the history of the different intonations given a handful of metaphors.</p></blockquote>', 69, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2021-05-19 15:36:01', '2021-05-19 15:36:01'),
(276, '<blockquote><p>Jameson does not claim that Lewis consciously pattered his character on this basis but  that literature is a privileged medium by means of which more abstract forces, particularly transnational ones that are beyond the threshold of conscious experience, can be made to be felt.</p></blockquote>', 68, NULL, '58', NULL, '2021-05-19 15:46:03', '2021-05-19 15:46:03'),
(277, '<blockquote><p>Jameson explains that this conceptualization of narrative form, the national allegory, does not establish some kind of homology or correspondence with historical events but rather functions \"as an instable and provisory solution to aesthetic dilemma which is itself the manifestation of a social and historical contradiction\" (<em>Fables of Aggression </em>94)</p></blockquote>', 68, NULL, '59', NULL, '2021-05-19 16:02:04', '2021-05-19 16:02:04'),
(278, '<p>three conditions that make the avant-garde possible: (1) \"Codification of a highly formalized academicism [...] with itself was institutionalized within official regimes of states and society still massively pervaded, often dominated, by aristocratic or landowning classes\"; (2) \"The still incipient, hence essentially novel, emergence within these societies of the key technologies or inventions of the second industrial revolution: telephone, radio, automobile, aircraft, and so on,\" which had not yet transformed the art work into a finished technified product as in postmodernism. ... and (3) \"The imaginative proximity of social revolution.\" [cited in Anderson, Parry p.34: <em>A zone of Engagement</em>]</p>', 68, NULL, '61', NULL, '2021-05-19 22:44:54', '2021-05-19 22:44:54'),
(279, '<p>...Bürger proposes that the institutionalization of art as a realm separate from the rest of life only unfolded to is perfection in the aestheticism of the late nineteenth century, thus constituting the precondition for the avant-garde to recognize art\'s full accommodation to bourgeois ideology. This recognition opened the way to a will to reconnect art and life (Bürger 17).</p><p>The problem buried in these accounts of the avant-gardes and their antagonism to the institutionalization of art is that the avant-gardes are not just an expression of the \"unfolding\" of bourgeois art. The rejection of institutionalization also stems from the embrace of other life experiences, such as those of subordinates classes and regions as well as colonized people.</p>', 68, NULL, '62', NULL, '2021-05-19 23:08:28', '2021-05-19 23:08:28'),
(280, '<p>If the oligarchies were tied to Europeanizing and liberal traditions, the avant-gardes sought native, popular, and anti-liberal means of social change.</p>', 68, NULL, '72', NULL, '2021-05-20 01:12:34', '2021-05-20 01:12:34'),
(281, '<p>...some \"peripheral\" avant-gardes attempted to overcome subordination by creating new cultural forms that could compete, against great odds, in a global cultural market.<br></p>', 68, NULL, '75', NULL, '2021-05-20 01:35:24', '2021-05-20 01:35:24'),
(282, '<blockquote><p>During the 1950s and early \'60s the school followed a French curriculum, but in the mid-1960s analytical inquiries into local heritage gave form to a new and alternative educational model--one that explored the potency of homegrown visual and material traditions to respond to the demands of modernity. The faculty reexamined its syllabi and introduced classes on the local history and practice of weaving, carpet and jewelry making, and ceramics. ...[16]</p><p>In Morocco, the turn toward abstraction was a political reorientation away from the French Orientalist school of painting and toward a methodology that had historical relevance and could be identified with the local culture prior to its transformation by colonization.[17]</p><p></p></blockquote>', 70, NULL, '16-17', NULL, '2021-05-23 19:21:07', '2021-05-23 20:05:40'),
(283, '<blockquote><p>So, in their quest to decolonize culture in the North African context, these artists pursued abstraction not as a counterpoint to representational painting as such but to push against the very particular manifestation of representational painting that had been practiced in the Maghreb under European colonial rule.</p></blockquote>', 70, NULL, '17', NULL, '2021-05-23 20:15:46', '2021-05-23 20:15:46'),
(284, '<p>Berkeley believed that</p><p>knowledge existed only in the mind of the knower. Thus, he answered in the negative the</p><p>hypothetical question about the sound of a tree falling in the forest when no one is there</p><p>to hear it.</p>', 71, NULL, '1', NULL, '2021-06-05 00:46:44', '2021-06-05 00:46:44'),
(285, '<p>Proponents of constructivism argue that learners construct knowledge</p><p>as they learn; they don\'t simply add new facts to what is known, but constantly reorganise</p><p>and create both understanding and the ability to learn as they interact with the world.</p><p>Further, the knowledge that is constructed through this process is individual or social, but</p><p>has no ontological status outside the mind of the knower.</p>', 71, NULL, '4', NULL, '2021-06-05 01:15:27', '2021-06-05 01:15:27'),
(286, '<p>In contrast, proponents of the constructivist</p><p>museum would argue that:</p><p>1. The viewer constructs personal knowledge from the exhibit</p><p>2. The process of gaining knowledge is itself a constructive act (7)</p><p>Examples of constructivist museums are harder to find, but exhibits that allow visitors to</p><p>draw their own conclusions about the meaning of the exhibition are based on this</p><p>constructivist principle.</p>', 71, NULL, '5', NULL, '2021-06-05 01:22:08', '2021-06-05 01:22:08'),
(287, '<blockquote><p>Finally, this wider historical perspective permits us to see that the process of decolonization did not necessarily involve the rejection or negation of imperialism, nor did it cause empires to entirely disappear from the scene. More often than not, they simply reconstituted themselves in new forms.</p></blockquote>', 64, NULL, '6', NULL, '2021-06-06 03:06:53', '2021-06-06 03:06:53'),
(288, '<blockquote><p>So much of what decolonization realized--and failed to realize--remain relevant to the global challenges we face today.</p></blockquote>', 64, NULL, '7', NULL, '2021-06-06 20:25:47', '2021-06-06 20:25:47'),
(289, '<blockquote><p>What binds them--and us--together id the spirit of nothingness.</p></blockquote>', 72, NULL, '8', NULL, '2021-06-06 20:48:06', '2021-06-06 20:48:06'),
(290, '<p>art is a privileged medium by means of which more abstract forces, particularly transnational ones that are beyond the threshold of conscious experience, can be made to be felt.</p>', 68, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2021-06-07 19:46:22', '2021-06-07 19:46:22'),
(291, '<p>Phenomenology’, writes Giorgi (1971, p.9), ‘is the study of phenomena as experienced by man. The primary emphasis is on the phenomenon itself exactly as it reveals itself to the experiencing subject in all its concreteness and particularity.’ Phenomenology explores the things and events of daily experience. Keen</p>', 74, NULL, '16', NULL, '2021-08-01 22:13:07', '2021-08-01 22:13:07'),
(292, '<p>Its task is less to give us new ideas than to make explicit those ideas, assumptions, and implicit presuppositions upon which we already behave and experience life. Its task is to reveal to us exactly what we already know and that we know it, so that we can be less puzzled about ourselves (1975, p. 18) keen</p>', 74, NULL, '16', NULL, '2021-08-01 22:14:35', '2021-08-01 22:14:35'),
(293, '<p>The world of the natural attitude is generally called by the phenomenologist lifeworld — the taken-for- granted pattern and context of everyday life through which the person routinely conducts his day-to-day existence without having to make it an object of conscious attention (Buttimer, 1976, pp.277, 281).</p>', 74, NULL, '16', NULL, '2021-08-01 22:30:43', '2021-08-01 22:30:43'),
(294, '<p>In the natural attitude we are too much absorbed by our mundane pursuits, both practical and theoretical; we are too much absorbed by our goals, purposes, and designs, to pay attention to the way the world presents itself to us. The acts of consciousness through which the world and whatever it contains become accessible to us are lived, but they remain undisclosed, unthematized, and in this sense concealed (Giorgi, 1970, p.148, italics in original).</p><p></p>', 74, NULL, '20', NULL, '2021-08-01 22:32:58', '2021-08-01 22:32:58'),
(295, '<p>— the phenomenologist seeks to make the lifeworld a focus of attention: ‘the acts which in the natural attitude are simply lived are now thematized and made topics of reflective analysis’ (Giorgi, 1970, p. 148). An important tool in this reductive process is epoche —</p><p>the suspension of belief in the experience or experienced thing. The phenomenologist attempts to disengage himself from the lifeworld and</p><p>re-examine its nature afresh in epoche — ‘to bring. . .precognitive “givens” into consciousness. . .and enable one to empathize with the worlds of other people’ (Buttimer, 1976, p.281)</p>', 74, NULL, '26', NULL, '2021-08-01 22:37:17', '2021-08-01 22:37:17'),
(296, '<p>Thinking is neither a line drawn be? tween subject and object nor a revolving of one around the other. Rather, thinking takes place in the relationship of territory and the earth</p>', 75, NULL, '87', NULL, '2021-08-08 20:43:24', '2021-08-08 20:43:24'),
(297, '<p>The earth is not one element among others but rather brings together all the elements within a single embrace while using one or an? other of them to deterritorialize territory. Move-</p>', 75, NULL, '87', NULL, '2021-08-08 21:00:06', '2021-08-08 21:00:06'),
(298, '<blockquote><p>Apparently, if one model of the old avant-garde was the Party à la Lenin, today the equivalent is a party à la Lennon.</p></blockquote>', 76, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2021-08-26 16:00:21', '2021-08-26 16:00:21'),
(299, '<p>space always under construction. space is a product of relations-between, relations which are necessarily embedded material practices which have to carried out, it is always in the process of being made. it never finished, never closed. we could imagined space as simultaneity of stories-so-far.</p>', 78, NULL, '9', NULL, '2021-10-10 05:34:16', '2021-10-10 05:34:16'),
(300, '<p>It is probably this surprising capacity for survival by absorbing part of the ciritique that has helped to disarm anti-capitalist forces. The paradoxical consequence is that in periods when capitalism seems triumphant--as is the case today--it displays a fragility that emerges precisely when real competitors have disappeared.</p>', 79, NULL, 'ch1 44/66', NULL, '2021-10-16 19:02:28', '2021-10-16 19:02:28'),
(301, '<blockquote><p>The artistic critique is anti-modernist when it stresses disenchantment, and modernist when it is concerned with liberation. (61/66)</p><p>...</p><p>The social ciritique is rather modernist when it underscores inequalities and anti-modernist when, fixing on the lack of solidarity, it is constructed as a critique of indivisualism.</p></blockquote>', 79, NULL, 'ch1 61/66', NULL, '2021-10-16 22:52:57', '2021-10-16 22:55:03'),
(302, '<blockquote><p> \'Traditions\' which appear or claim to be old are often quite recent in origin and sometimes invented.</p></blockquote>', 80, NULL, '1', NULL, '2021-11-06 01:53:49', '2021-11-06 01:53:49'),
(303, '<blockquote><p>\'Invented tradition\' is taken to mean a set of practices, normally governed by overtly or tacitly accepted rules and of a ritual or symbolic nature, which seek to inculcate certain values and norms of behaviour by repetition, which automatically implies continuity with the past.</p></blockquote>', 80, NULL, '1', NULL, '2021-11-06 02:10:29', '2021-11-06 02:10:29'),
(304, '<blockquote><p>It is the contrast between thhe constant change and innovation of the modern world and the attempt to structure at least some parts of social life within it as unchanging and invariant, that makes the \'invention of tradition\' so interesting for historicans of the past two centuries.</p></blockquote>', 80, NULL, '2', NULL, '2021-11-06 02:17:42', '2021-11-06 02:17:42'),
(305, '<blockquote><p>The past, real or invented, to which they refer imposes fixed (normally formalized) practices, such as repetition.</p></blockquote>', 80, NULL, '2', NULL, '2021-11-06 02:21:10', '2021-11-06 02:21:10'),
(306, '<blockquote><p>\'Custom\' in traditional societies has the double function of motor and fly-wheel. It does not preclude innovation and change up to a point, though evidentaly the requirement that it must appear compatible or even identical with thre precedent imposes substantial limitations on it. ... \'Custom\' cannot afford to be invariant, because even in \'traditional\' societies life is not so. [2] ...\'Custom\' is what judges do; \'tradition\' (in this instance invented tradition) is the wig, robe and other formal paraphernalia and ritualized practices surrounding their substantial action. The decline of \'custom\' inevitably changes the \'tradition\' with which it is habitually intertwined.</p></blockquote>', 80, NULL, '2-3', NULL, '2021-11-06 02:38:28', '2021-11-06 02:38:28'),
(307, '<blockquote><p>Inventing traditions, it is assumed here, is essentially a process of formalization and ritualization, characterized by reference to the past, if only by imposing repetition.</p></blockquote>', 80, NULL, '4', NULL, '2021-11-06 03:14:30', '2021-11-06 03:14:30'),
(308, '<blockquote><p>...we should expect it to occur more frequently when a rapid transformation of society weakens or destroys the social patterns for which \'old\' traditions had been designed, producing new ones to which they were noy applicable, or when such old traditions and ther instituitional carroers and promulgators no longer prove sufficently adaptable and flexible, or are otherwise eliminated: in short, when there are sufficently large and rapid changes on the demand or the supply side.</p></blockquote>', 80, NULL, '5', NULL, '2021-11-06 18:18:20', '2021-11-06 18:18:20'),
(309, '<blockquote><p>Existing customary traditional practices--folksong, physical contests, marksmanship--were modified, ritualized and instituitionalized for the new national purposes.</p></blockquote>', 80, NULL, '6', NULL, '2021-11-06 18:32:27', '2021-11-06 18:32:27'),
(310, '<blockquote><p>Such a break is visible even in movements deliberately describing themeselves as \'traditionalists\', and appealing to groups which were, by common consent, regarded as the repositories of historic continuity and tradition, such as peasants.</p></blockquote>', 80, NULL, '7', NULL, '2021-11-06 19:13:42', '2021-11-06 19:13:42'),
(311, '<blockquote><p>Yet it may be suggested that were they [traditions] are invented, it is often not because old ways are no longer available or viable, but because they are deliberately not used or adapted.</p></blockquote>', 80, NULL, '8', NULL, '2021-11-06 19:24:31', '2021-11-06 19:24:31'),
(312, '<p>Thus, in consciously setting itself against tradition and for radical innovation, the nineteenth-century libral ideology of social change systematically failed to provide for the social and authority ties taken for granted in earlier societies, and created voids which might have to be filled by invented practices.</p>', 80, NULL, '8', NULL, '2021-11-06 19:32:18', '2021-11-06 19:32:18'),
(313, '<blockquote><p>...most of occasions when people became conscious of citizenship as such remain associated with symbols and semi-ritual practices (for instance, elections), most of which are historically novel and largely invented: flags, images, ceremonies and music.</p></blockquote>', 80, NULL, '12', NULL, '2021-11-06 21:41:59', '2021-11-06 21:41:59'),
(314, '<blockquote><p>...all invented traditions, so far as possible, use history as a legitimator of action and cement of group cohesion.</p></blockquote>', 80, NULL, '12', NULL, '2021-11-06 21:45:34', '2021-11-06 21:45:34'),
(315, '<p>Yet all historicans, whatever else their objectives, are engaged in this process inasmych as they contribute, consciously or not, to the creation, dismmantling and restructuring of images of the past which belong not only to the world of specialist investigation but to the public sphere of man as a political being.</p>', 80, NULL, '13', NULL, '2021-11-07 05:18:04', '2021-11-07 05:18:04'),
(316, '<p>We should not be misled by a curious, but understandable, paradox: modern nations and all theit impedimenta generally claim to be the opposite of novel, namely rooted in the remotest antiquity, and the opposite of constructed, namely human communities so \'natural\' as to require no definition other than self-assertion.</p>', 80, NULL, '14', NULL, '2021-11-07 05:34:36', '2021-11-07 05:34:36'),
(317, '<blockquote><p>After the 1870s, therefore, and almost certainly in connection with the emergence of mass politics, rulers and middle-class observers rediscovered the importance of \'irrational\' elements in the maintenance of the social fabric and the social order.</p></blockquote>', 81, NULL, '268', NULL, '2021-11-08 19:16:36', '2021-11-08 19:16:36'),
(318, '<blockquote><p>The intellectual study of politics and society was transformed by the recognition that whatever held human collectivities together it was not the rational calculation of their individual members.</p></blockquote>', 81, NULL, '268-9', NULL, '2021-11-08 19:20:49', '2021-11-08 19:20:49'),
(319, '<blockquote><p>In terms of the invention of tradition, three major innovation are particularly relevant. The first was the development of a secular equivalent of the church ... The second was the invention of public ceremonies. ... A less permanent form of public celebration were the occasional world expositions whihc gave the Republic the legitimacy of prosperity, technical progrss--the Eiffel Tower--and the global colonial conquest they took care to emphasize.</p></blockquote>', 81, NULL, '271', NULL, '2021-11-08 21:25:36', '2021-11-08 21:25:36'),
(320, '<blockquote><p>The response to the Celebrations from the press was generally neither overwhelmingly negative nor positive, but a numbr of journalists were openly hostile to the event, and their accounts are those most vividly remembered. Furthermore, the presence of so many heads of state in an exotic location and the resulting heightened media attention gave rise to sensationalism as journalists speculated widly, particularly about the cost.</p></blockquote>', 82, NULL, '3', NULL, '2021-11-09 17:38:14', '2021-11-09 17:38:14'),
(321, '<blockquote><p>\"What an absurd, bathetic spectacle! The son of a colonel in a Persian Cossack regiment play-acting as the emperor of a country with an average per capita income of $250 per year, proclaiming his achievements in modernizing his nation while accoutred in the raiment and symbols of ancient despotism. No wonder we talked among ourselves about the fragility of an anachronistic structure that compounded the doubtful expectancy of an absolute monarch with wasteful display. It was, I thought, a deliberate insult to the wretchedly poor with whom the country abounded. Still, though the prodigality of Versailles had nothing on the Golestan Palace, the greatest affront was not to come until four years later. Then the Shah and his queen spent $120 million on an opulent pageant at Persepolis that enriched not Omar the Tentmaker, but Pierre the Tentmaker and the other luxury merchants of Paris who handled the arrangements. A few minor heads of state showed up to keep company with Spiro Agnew, but the world was either too polite or too humourless to laugh.\"</p></blockquote><p>(George Ball, The Past Has Another Pattern (New York: Norton, 1982), 435–6.)</p>', 82, NULL, '3', NULL, '2021-11-09 18:06:03', '2021-11-09 18:07:02'),
(322, '<p>Many historians and commentators have claimed that the Celebrations were one of the root causes of the revolution, and that they helped to cement the image of the Shah as a delusional, out-of-touch third-world autocrat.</p>', 82, NULL, '5', NULL, '2021-11-09 18:26:20', '2021-11-09 18:26:20'),
(323, '<blockquote><p>This book aims show how cultural politics, in other words, the shaping of politics through the use of culture, helped to promote the Pahlavi national ideology.</p></blockquote>', 82, NULL, '7', NULL, '2021-11-09 19:16:54', '2021-11-09 19:16:54');
INSERT INTO `codes` (`id`, `body`, `reference_id`, `notes`, `pages`, `deleted_at`, `created_at`, `updated_at`) VALUES
(324, '<blockquote><p>Special committees were established in countries  around the world to direct programmes of activities and according to published figures there were as many as 131 books on various aspects of Iranian civilization and culture published, and 143 exhibitions, 326 congresses, seminars and other academic proceedings and 37 artistic events held, including poetry readings and ballet, theatre and classical music performances.38 Some of these publications and events were supported financially or logistically by the Iranian state, but many more were initiated independently of Iranian state influence.</p></blockquote>', 82, NULL, '7', NULL, '2021-11-09 21:59:55', '2021-11-09 21:59:55'),
(325, '<blockquote><p>The Shah\'s Imperial Celebration, too, were a clear articulation of what the Pahlavi state believed it meant to be Iranian, and though some were undoubtedly convinced, many were not, and the event broadened and intensified discussion about the nation and monarchical rule.</p></blockquote>', 82, NULL, '8', NULL, '2021-11-09 22:11:15', '2021-11-09 22:11:15'),
(326, '<p>This books draws on a wide range of primary source materials, including academic publications, official documents, newspapers,...</p>', 82, NULL, '10', NULL, '2021-11-09 22:40:35', '2021-11-09 22:40:35'),
(327, '<p>Among archives and libraries consulted during the research for this book were the British National Archives and the British Museum in London, the Institute of Social History in Amsterdam, the National Archives of the Netherlands in The Hague, the Austrian Staatsarchiv in Vienna, and the Bibliothequ universitaire des langues et civilisation in Paris, which holds the archive of Shoja al-Din Shafa,</p>', 82, NULL, '10', NULL, '2021-11-09 22:44:36', '2021-11-15 01:26:17'),
(328, '<blockquote><p>It will show that the Celebrations became an important rallying point for disparate opposition group voicing long-standing grievances against the Shah\'s regime.</p></blockquote>', 82, NULL, '12', NULL, '2021-11-09 23:37:35', '2021-11-09 23:37:35');
